<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Changes benefit retail investors - Derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Individual investors will benefit most from the Chancellor's efforts to
clarify the tax treatment of some futures and options products.
Under the changes announced in the Budget, investors buying an options
contract for which they make an upfront payment called a 'premium', will be
able to offset the cost of this against capital gains tax. This applies to
cash-settled options bringing them into line with rules that already apply
to similar instruments.
Futures industry officials say this takes away a current disincentive for
individual investors to invest in derivatives, but is not likely in itself
to entice waves of new investors into the industry.
In addition, the chancellor announced a review of the taxation of interest
in an attempt to remove anomalies between the treatment of derivatives and
their underlying instruments.
Other measures taken in the derivatives sector were largely technical
clarifications of the treatment by companies of foreign exchange and futures
and options gains and losses in advance of new regulations which are due to
be published later in December.
'This is a very sensible move and reduces risk for the professional
operator, but it is not going to encourage retail investors to use options
until they can understand them,' said Mr Charles Fry, chairman of Johnson
Fry, which runs a Pounds 4m futures fund.
</TEXT>
