<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Government bond prices given boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK government bond prices were boosted yesterday by the chancellor's
announcement that there would be a Pounds 6.8bn reduction in official sales
of gilt-edged stock during the next 18 months, because of a policy change
announced in the last Budget, Conner Middelmann writes.
The long-dated gilt futures contract rose sharply, from 115 25/32 just
before the speech to close at 116 5/8 . It rallied further to 116 29/32 in
after-hours trading.
In the March Budget the then chancellor, Mr Norman Lamont, announced that
sales of gilts to banks and building societies from 1993-94 onwards would
count towards the funding of the borrowing requirement in the same way as
sales to other institutions.
He also announced a second measure designed to help the government fund its
borrowing requirement. He said that any gilt sales to banks and building
societies which had already been made in 1992-93 would be used to reduce
funding requirements over the following two to three years - though at that
stage it was not known how much had been sold to these institutions.
Mr Clarke said yesterday that Pounds 6.8bn had been raised by gilt sales to
banks and building societies in 1992-93. He added that none of this had yet
been used in the government's current funding operations.
As a result, gilt sales between now and the end of 1994-95 will be Pounds
6.8bn lower than would otherwise have been the case, he said.
'This was the announcement that kick-started the market yesterday,' said Mr
Chris Anthony, gilts analyst at UBS.
Lowering next year's gross gilt issuance by Pounds 6.8bn 'reduces the risk
that things will go sour', he added, meaning that the government could
otherwise have had difficulty making gilt sales.
Funding for the current financial year has gone relatively smoothly, with
some Pounds 43bn of the total Pounds 50bn PSBR covered so far.
</TEXT>
