<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Clarke committed to erasing budget deficit by
year 2000 - Medium-term outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALEXANDER NICOLL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Budget announced yesterday differs markedly from its March predecessor
in its medium-term projection of a steady fall in the public sector
borrowing requirement from Pounds 50bn this year, almost to zero by the end
of the decade.
Mr Kenneth Clarke's explicit commitment to erasing the budget deficit is
based both on projections of lower public spending - as well as a
significant increase in revenue - and also on a slightly more optimistic
picture of the medium-term prospects for the economy.
Mr Norman Lamont, the previous chancellor, had forecast a progressive but
more modest fall in the PSBR to 3.75 per cent of GDP by 1997/98.
The Treasury's Red Book forecast yesterday that the economy would grow by an
average of 3 per cent per year over the medium term, and that inflation as
measured by the GDP deflator would drop to 2 per cent by the 1998/99 fiscal
year from 4 per cent in 1994/95. In March, it had predicted average economic
growth of around 2.5 per cent, and inflation expectations were almost the
same as yesterday's.
Retail price inflation excluding mortgage interest payments is forecast to
rise slightly to 3.25 per cent next financial year from 3 per cent this
year, but then to drop steadily to 2 per cent by 1998/99. The Treasury said
spare capacity would continue to exert downward pressure on inflation.
The Treasury noted that 'the pace at which the PSBR declines will depend
significantly on the growth of the economy over the medium term'.
It said that if the economy were to grow faster than expected, by an average
of 3.5 per cent per year in the medium term, the PSBR would be eliminated by
1997/98. But if it grew by an average of 2.5 per cent, the PSBR would still
be 2 per cent of GDP in 1998/99.
Spending cuts and substantial tax revenue increases both contribute to the
rapid projected fall in the PSBR.
The measures announced yesterday reduce projected public spending by Pounds
3.6bn in the next financial year and Pounds 1.5bn and Pounds 2.9bn in the
following two years respectively, compared with plans announced in the March
1993 budget.
They also raise expected revenue from taxes and national insurance
contributions by Pounds 1.7bn, Pounds 4.9bn and Pounds 6.1bn in the next
three financial years respectively.
The Treasury projects that general government expenditure as a percentage of
GDP will fall from 45 per cent this year to 41 per cent in 1998/99.
It noted that spending as a proportion of the economy, which had been on a
downward trend for much of the 1980s, has risen in recent years because of
the recession. It is now projected to fall from 1994/95 onwards.
These reductions are accompanied by significant cuts in the expected amount
of interest to be paid on government debt from 1994/95 onwards. In that
year, interest is forecast at Pounds 22.5bn, Pounds 0.8bn lower than
previously forecast. The figures for succeeding years of Pounds 24.5bn,
Pounds 25.6bn, Pounds 26.5bn are respectively Pounds 1.3bn, Pounds 2.5bn and
Pounds 3bn lower than previously forecast. For 1997/98, interest is
projected at Pounds 27bn.
The Treasury said, however, that public sector debt as a proportion of GDP
would continue to rise, and would peak at 44 per cent before beginning to
fall in 1997/98.
On the revenue side, the Treasury forecasts that general government receipts
as a pro portion of GDP will rise from 36 per cent of GDP this year to 40.25
per cent in 1998/99.
The Treasury said the economic recovery, as well as previously announced tax
increases, should reverse the recent fall in government receipts as a
proportion of the GDP. Corporation tax, for example, had halved as a
proportion of GDP during the past four years. 'This should be reversed in
the upswing, albeit gradually given the lags in tax collection and
assessment.'
Big increases in tax revenues will start to appear in 1995/96, according to
the Treasury's projections. Taxes on income, expenditure and capital are
forecast in that year at Pounds 220bn, compared with Pounds 212bn projected
in the March Red Book.
By 1997/98, this measure of tax revenue is forecast at Pounds 254bn, a
Pounds 13bn increase from the March estimate.
For 1998/99, total tax revenue is forecast at Pounds 341bn, and total
government spending at Pounds 345bn, giving a general government borrowing
requirement of Pounds 4bn. But after taking account of borrowing by public
corporations, the PSBR would be only Pounds 2bn.
</TEXT>
