<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Economy expected to show gradual recovery -
Forecasts for next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A picture of an economy picking up steam slowly but perhaps unevenly next
year was painted by the government yesterday in forecasts accompanying the
Budget statement.
The forecasts also suggested a slight rise next year in inflation, chiefly
caused by tax rises, and a significantly lower public sector borrowing
requirement.
The government also predicted that the current account deficit will be more
comfortably under control than had been envisaged in its previous forecasts
issued in March.
Inflation was seen as remaining subdued, however. The retail price index -
excluding mortgage interest payments - was forecast to rise from 3 per cent
this year to 3 1/4 per cent next.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, predicted 1994 growth of 2 1/2 per cent -
at the bottom of the range expected by most private forecasters  - after an
expected growth rate this year of 1 3/4 per cent. This year's growth has
been faster than the 1 1/4 per cent forecast by the Treasury in March.
Excluding expanding oil output from the North Sea, 1994 growth was forecast
at 2 1/4 per cent.
The economy has grown steadily - by 2 1/2 per cent - in six successive
quarters since the trough of the recession that the Treasury now says
occurred in the first quarter of 1992. That was, Mr Clarke noted, well
before sterling's departure from the Exchange Rate Mechanism in September
last year.
However, this picture of steady recovery might change. 'While the recovery
so far has been remarkably smooth, it would not be surprising if the profile
of output were more uneven from now on,' the Treasury said in the Red Book
which goes with the Budget.
Next year, as in this, consumers will continue to play a key role in the
continuation of economic expansion. Consumer spending should expand 2 1/4
per cent in the coming year, after its expected 2 per cent growth this.
Government consumption - flat this year - should grow by 1 per cent, while
investment is predicted to grow by 3 per cent next year after its sluggish
expansion this year of  1/2 per cent.
Robust export growth - 5 3/4 per cent against 4 per cent this year - is also
foreseen in 1994, while the pace of import expansion should pick up to 5 1/4
per cent compared with 2 per cent.
The Treasury left unchanged its estimate for the normally-volatile public
sector borrowing requirement for the current financial year at the Pounds
50bn forecast in March. However, there was a marked drop forecast in the
PSBR for 1994-5: as a result of Budget measures and the economic recovery,
it is seen as likely to fall to Pounds 38bn in 1994-95.
Many economists in the City of London viewed Mr Clarke as having credibly
paved the way for a significant drop in government borrowing while managing
to avoid puncturing a fragile economic recovery.
Mr Neil Mackinnon, of Citibank, said the tax increases proposed in the
budget 'can be absorbed by the economy without undermining the
sustainability of the recovery'. Inflation also looked encouraging, given
that there was no extension of the scope of value added tax.
Others, however, saw the budget as implying a significant tightening of
fiscal policy, which suggested the government was too sanguine about growth
prospects - unless further interest rate cuts were on the way.
Mr James Barty, chief UK economist at Morgan Grenfell, cut his forecast for
1994 growth to 2 per cent, saying that yesterday's budget and the previous
one in March had together 'designed a headwind for the UK economy'.
That would be surmounted only by further cuts in interest rates and a
competitive exchange rate. Mr Roger Bootle, economist with Midland Global
Markets, concurred that 'the Bank of England might want another half per
cent cut in interest rates . . . soon.'
The government forecasts show the Treasury was unduly pessimistic in March
in predicting a current account deficit of Pounds 17 1/2 bn for the current
year and of Pounds 18 1/2 bn (annualised) for the first half of 1994.
The deficit for 1992 was revised down to Pounds 8bn (from the Pounds 12bn in
March). 'Despite a fallback in the invisible surplus and stronger growth in
the UK than in Continental Europe, our main export market, the current
account deficit is expected to increase only slightly in 1993. It is
forecast to be Pounds 9 1/2 bn in both 1993 and 1994.' The numbers may also
have been influenced by a newly-introduced system of recording trade with
the European Union.
The Budget measures included spending cuts for the coming year of more than
Pounds 3 1/2 bn, Mr Clarke said. Mr John Shepperd, UK economist at Yamaichi,
the Japanese investment bank, described the Pounds 3.6bn cut as a 'rabbit
out of the hat but one has to ask whether it is achievable.'
Mr Richard Jeffrey, head of research at Charterhouse Tilney, said the
spending reductions were credible in that 'government expenditure is more
cyclical than had been allowed for in March.' For example, unemployment had
fallen faster than expected.
The Treasury said the recovery so far has been accompanied by a labour
productivity performance 'which was abnormally strong for a cyclical
downturn, perhaps reflecting the effects of labour market reforms.'
While the recent drop in unemployment was associated with slowing
productivity growth, non-oil productivity was still 3 3/4 per cent up on a
year earlier, and manufacturing productivity in the third quarter was 5 per
cent up. 'As the recovery becomes more established, annual productivity
growth could fall further from its recent high rates,' the Treasury said.
The Chancellor outlined two main risks to what he described as encouraging
prospects for 1994. The first was continuing weakness of world economic
activity, particularly in Europe.
'What manufacturing industry needs most is a pick up of activity in the rest
of Europe', he said.
The second major risk was the public finances. 'The overriding need is to
place the public finances on a sound footing. That is the immediate task of
the government and the main theme of my Budget today,' he said.
The government forecasts assume oil prices are assumed to average Dollars 17
a barrel.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
