<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Cut of Pounds 60m brings harmony closer -
Scottish non-domestic rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Scottish businesses are to have their total non-domestic rates bill cut by a
further Pounds 60m as a result of the Budget, as part of the policy of
gradually harmonising non-domestic rates in Scotland with the uniform
business rate in England and Wales. The process entails reducing Scotland's
higher levels of business rates to the lower English levels and has been
going on since 1989.
It involves periodic injections of money from the Scottish Office to offset
the revenue which local authorities would otherwise forego with the lower
rates income. In Scotland the Scottish secretary sets each council's
non-domestic rates poundage.
Since 1989 the non-domestic rates burden in Scotland has been reduced by
Pounds 500m. With yesterday's announcement, four more of Scotland's 65
councils will join the three whose rates had already fallen to English
levels.
The gap remaining to be filled after the Budget comes into effect should be
about Pounds 70m.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said yesterday that he was contributing
Pounds 47.5m of the Pounds 60m reduction to the councils. They will be
expected to save Pounds 12.5m through efficiency measures to achieve the
Pounds 60m reduction for the rate payers.
Mr Lang said yesterday's reduction in rate poundages was Pounds 10m greater
than it would otherwise have been, thanks to Scotland's Pounds 10m share of
the overall reduction in business rates announced by Mr Clarke in the
Budget.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
