<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Invalidity benefit scrapped
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Invalidity benefit is to disappear and be replaced by a more tightly
controlled incapacity benefit aimed strictly at those genuinely incapable of
work.
Alterations to invalidity benefit in the Budget had been widely expected. It
had become one of the fastest growing social security benefits - over the
past 10 years numbers of people claiming it have risen from 700,000 to 1.5m,
with expenditure doubling in real terms to Pounds 6bn a year. This was set
to reach Pounds 8bn by 1995-96.
Ministers have increasingly expressed the view, repeated by Mr Kenneth
Clarke yesterday, that the benefit was being claimed by 'many people who are
not genuine invalids'.
The new benefit, to be introduced in April 1995, will replace both
invalidity benefit and sickness benefit. Incapacity benefit, unlike
invalidity benefit, will be taxed, bringing it into line with other income
replacement benefits such as retirement pensions.
Mr Clarke said the new benefit will be subject to a 'tighter and more
objective medical test'. This may bring the government into conflict with
the medical profession. The British Medical Association conference this year
angrily rejected government suggestions that an over-lenient approach by GPs
was fuelling the rapid growth in invalidity benefit.
</TEXT>
