<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Help for elderly averts rebellion - Pensioners'
aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chancellor appeared to have averted the possibility of a backbench
rebellion over VAT on fuel with the announcement of his compensation package
for all pensioners irrespective of whether they are on income support.
It was warmly welcomed by backbenchers concerned about the government's
decision to press ahead with its plan to impose VAT on domestic fuel at 8
per cent in April and 17.5 per cent the following year.
Sir John Hannam, secretary of the powerful 1922 backbench committee,
expressed his relief that the chancellor had widened the compensation
package to all pensioners. 'That was what people were really concerned
about,' he said.
His prediction there would be little trouble from backbenchers over the
package was underlined by comments from some of the more independently
minded Tory MPs with trenchant views on the subject.
Mr Nicholas Winterton, (Macclesfield), said that while he would have
preferred the government to have changed its decision to impose VAT on
domestic fuel, he was nonetheless pleased with the compensation.
'It is rather better than expected since the chancellor has agreed to give
assistance to pensioners who are not on income support,' he said.
Mr Winston Churchill, (Davyhulme), said: 'The key thing is that the people
who have saved over the years are going to get help with their fuel bills.'
Ms Edwina Currie, (Derbyshire South), commended the chancellor for
'political astuteness' in widening the compensation to include all
pensioners.
Conservative backbenchers also welcomed the further special increases for
poorer pensioners and the disabled.
Criticism of the package was left to Mr John Smith, Labour leader, who said
the compensation was 'not adequate' since pensioners would get only half the
extra cost.
</TEXT>
