<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: 'Son of BES' to boost investment - Small
companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chancellor has attempted to stimulate equity investment in small
companies by setting up a successor to the controversial Business Expansion
Scheme (BES), and proposing a new scheme to encourage venture capital
investments.
His measures were welcomed by banks that have provided the overdraft and
short-term debt finance which has been used as a substitute for equity by
small companies.
Many had called for the chancellor to devise a 'son of BES' scheme. The
Enterprise Investment Scheme (EIS) announced in the Budget will follow the
BES in offering income tax relief on equity investments in unquoted trading
companies, but will exclude investments in private rented housing.
The BES, which is due to end in December, was originally limited in the same
manner, but became discredited after it was extended in 1988 to private
rented housing schemes, and turned largely into a tax avoidance vehicle.
It will also include a measure to encourage 'business angels' who introduce
finance to small companies by letting them become paid directors of the
companies they invest in without losing tax relief.
Mr Clarke's second measure to encourage equity investment - following
criticism from banks and small business groups that small companies are too
dependent on short-term finance - is to encourage a new form of venture
capital trust.
He is to issue a consultation paper in the new year which will propose a new
type of investment trust that would invest a big proportion of assets in
unquoted companies. Investors would gain tax relief on dividends and capital
gains.
Mr Clarke emphasised in his speech that the venture capital trust would
allow investors to limit the risk of investing in what is traditionally an
unstable market by diversifying their risk across a portfolio of small
companies.
The EIS will provide income tax relief at 20 per cent up to a maximum of
Pounds 100,000 a year and companies will be able to raise up to Pounds 1m a
year. The Exchequer estimated that EIS would cost Pounds 10m in the next
financial year.
</TEXT>
