<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Heating aid broader than expected - Compensating
for VAT on fuel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The package of measures to help low-income households with the higher
heating bills which will follow the extension of VAT to fuel and power was
extended more widely than many critics had expected.
In addition to providing extra payments for those on the lowest incomes who
receive means-tested benefits, the package includes an unexpected boost to
the basic state pension paid to almost all retired people. More than 15m
people will be included - including some relatively affluent pensioners.
The package was also sweetened with a new national savings investment for
pensioners which will provide them with a guaranteed - if unspecified -
monthly income over five years.
Cold weather payments, paid to pensioners, families with young children and
disabled people on income support during sharp spells of cold weather, will
rise from Pounds 6 a week to Pounds 7 from next winter and to Pounds 7.50
the following winter. And an extra Pounds 35m a year is to be put into the
Home Energy Efficiency Scheme which provide grants to insulate homes. The
scheme, currently limited to those on income support, will be extended to
all pensioners and disabled people.
The cost of the package will be Pounds 416m in 1994-95, following the
imposition of VAT on domestic fuel at 8 per cent on April 1 1994. When the
rate rises to the full 17 1/2 per cent level on April 1 1995, the cost of
the compensation measures will increase to Pounds 897m, and will reach
almost Pounds 1.3bn in 1996-97.
These figures are at the top end of estimates of what Mr Peter Lilley, the
social security secretary, would win from the chancellor.
The aid package was welcomed by some charities for the elderly, but Age
Concern warned the extra money would not be enough to compensate for higher
fuel bills.
Scottish charities and pressure groups have already claimed that VAT on fuel
will particularly affect people north of the border and that the poorest 10
per cent of the population will be hit seven times harder than the richest
10 per cent.
At the heart of the package are increases in social security benefits in
advance of the higher fuel bills. Normally, benefits would rise only after a
year of higher bills, in the annual uprating in line with prices.
All single pensioners will get an extra 50p a week from April 1994, in
addition to the normal uprating. Married couples will get 70p a week. A year
later, there will be the same increases again when VAT on fuel rises from 8
to 17 1/2 per cent.
The same increases will be paid to widows and those on invalidity benefit.
Those on means-tested income support who are not pensioners will receive
higher increases in April 1994 and 1995 to compensate for higher fuel
prices.
Relief factor, page 24
</TEXT>
