<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Air traffic control may be privatised - Aviation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is considering privatising air traffic control services to
help finance new civil aviation investment programmes.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, yesterday set up a working group of
officials to report by early 1994 on the possibility of transferring the
Civil Aviation Authority's National Air Traffic Service (NATS) operations to
the private sector.
An airline industry lobby has been campaigning for splitting air traffic
control services from the CAA, arguing that privatisation would make NATS
more cost-efficient and reduce airline charges. Opponents have said that
privatising these services, which employ about 5500 people, would raise
serious safety issues and that it was best for an independent government
agency like the CAA to retain control of these operations.
</TEXT>
