<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Local government a big loser - Public spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The moves to reduce the fiscal deficit shift a larger proportion of
Britain's public spending towards social security, health and education and
away from local government, transport, defence and public housing.
The biggest loser in the announcement of spending plans for the next three
years is spending by central government departments on local government,
which has been cut by Pounds 860m in 1994-95 compared with the plans set out
in the March Budget.
In 1994-95 spending by the chancellor's departments - including the Treasury
and the Central Statistical Office - has been shaved by Pounds 130m to
Pounds 3.43bn. This is part of the general drive to cut spending throughout
the civil service by low growth in wage costs and greater efficiency.
Relative winners have been central government spending on education and
health which have been boosted by Pounds 390m and Pounds 480m respectively
in 1994-95 compared with plans set out in March. The new totals for these
departments are Pounds 10.49bn and Pounds 31.73bn.
Defence spending has been reduced by Pounds 260m in 1994-95,while transport
has been cut by Pounds 210m with the roads programme a particular casualty.
Spending by the Department of the Environment on housing has been cut by
Pounds 250m.
In 1994-95, social security departmental spending has been increased by
Pounds 1.55bn compared with the total agreed in March, mainly due to higher
pensions and payments to poorer people hit by the imposition of VAT on fuel.
The new totals for central government spending on defence, transport and
housing in 1994-95 work out at Pounds 23.49bn, Pounds 5.85bn and Pounds
7.43bn. Social security spending - easily the biggest share of the total -
comes out at Pounds 68.8bn
The new figures are part of the public spending control total which in
1994-95 has been set at Pounds 251.3bn. Allowing for a classification change
linked to altered national accounting treatment of the fossil fuel levy, the
1994-95 figure is Pounds 3.6bn less than that set out in the March Budget.
Another way the Treasury has cut back spending is to have reduced the
unallocated reserve which is part of the 1994-95 control total from the
Pounds 7bn figure in the March Budget to Pounds 3.5bn.
Rather than spread the Pounds 3.5bn removed from reserve among spending
programmes - which has been the Treasury practice in comparable Budgets in
recent years - the department has taken the money out of public spending
altogether.
</TEXT>
<XX>
