<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Budget 93: Closing loopholes may save up to Pounds 2bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Payments in gold bars, coffee beans and manipulations of profit-related pay
formulae are among the choice options of tax avoiders that were killed in
the Budget. The chancellor closed a number of loopholes which he estimated
would save Pounds 2bn over the next three years.
The most significant proposals were:
Prevention of any artificial schemes to avoid pay-as-you-earn and National
Insurance contributions by paying staff in gold, coffee and other assets.
The estimated savings will be Pounds 200m in 1994-95 and a further Pounds
75m in 1995-96.
The change will stop such payments for pay-as-you-earn from the time of the
Finance Act next year. But the same schemes in use for National Insurance
contributions were cancelled from midnight.
Tightened regulations on profit-related pay to ensure that relief is
concentrated on genuine schemes for employees. The estimated savings will be
Pounds 40m in 1993-94 and Pounds 100m in 1994-95.
The amendments will increase the upper limit on profits which an employer
may disregard in calculating profit-related pay and remove disproportionate
status to special schemes favouring particular units within a business.
Only permitting indexation of capital gains in the future to extinguish a
capital gain, and not to create or increase a capital loss. This is expected
to raise Pounds 50m in 1994-95, rising to about Pounds 300m in 1996-97.
Preventing companies from being sold in circumstances to ensure that their
liabilities cannot be collected, which could save Pounds 100m.
Toughening up the conditions for companies that control foreign companies in
low tax areas overseas, estimated to save Pounds 50m.
Tightening abuses on stamp duty, which should save Pounds 60m in 1994-95.
The chancellor also ended a little known tax relief on payments made as a
result of extortion paid to criminals.
Mr Clarke said:
'The tax avoidance industry is always ingenious, but it is one industry
which this government has never helped.'
</TEXT>
