<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / US predicts outline trade deal: Kantor hopes for preliminary
agreement with EU by weekend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE, FRANCES WILLIAMS and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, GENEVA, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, predicted yesterday that the
US and the European Union would this week produce an outline of preliminary
agreements for the Uruguay Round of world trade talks, including deals on
agriculture and tariff cuts.
But Mr Kantor, speaking before leaving for Brussels, said there was 'grave
doubt' that he and his EU counterpart, Sir Leon Brittan, could produce a
complete draft text this week.
Mr Kantor's determination to conclude an outline deal within 48 hours was
shared in Brussels amid fresh signs that France was prepared to soften its
hardline stance.
France has shelved earlier threats to veto a trade-liberalising deal within
the framework of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. It signalled
its readiness to sign an agreement if 'French national interests are
protected'.
The French move follows warnings from Germany and the UK that failure to
reach a Gatt deal would jeopardise prospects for an economic recovery in
Europe and risk splitting the EU. Underlining German concern, Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and French prime minister Edouard Balladur agreed, on the
opening day of summit talks in Bonn yesterday, to work hand-in-hand for a
Gatt deal.
Mr Kantor, voicing optimism, said there was 'great flexibility' in talks on
market access for farm products. He also hinted that preliminary agreement
had been reached on rules for a new multinational trading organisation and
said there was 'great room for manoeuvrability' on the dispute over trade in
audiovisual products.
Mr Mike Espy, the US agriculture secretary, hinted that the Clinton
administration was prepared to modify its adamant refusal to renegotiate its
position on the Blair House accord on farm trade.
Mr Jacques Delors, the European Commission president, said, after addressing
a French parliament committee, that 'the Americans seem to be beginning to
budge' towards meeting European demands on reducing tariffs and liberalising
services.
Meanwhile, French farm union leaders vowed to step up their efforts to
prevent any retreat by France in its opposition to the Blair House
agreement.
Background, Page 4
</TEXT>
