<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / The Lex Column: Dividends
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Foreign Income Dividend scheme promised in the last budget has not
solved the problem of unrelieved advance corporation tax. As expected, the
new class of dividend will not carry the 20 per cent tax credit normally
reclaimed by pension funds on conventional dividends. Since the Treasury
will not allow different classes of dividend to be targeted at different
types of shareholder, companies which pay FIDs will risk the opprobrium of
this powerful group. Forcing companies to pay higher dividends to compensate
pension funds for the lost tax credit can hardly be what the chancellor had
in mind. Companies with intractable ACT problems will doubtless still look
hard at paying FIDs. Concessions made on the initial proposals at least make
the scheme look workable. Allowing companies to pay FIDs out of prior year
profits, for example, will help ensure that potentially volatile overseas
profits are available in all years to cover the payment. But alternative
methods for reducing ACT such as enhanced scrip dividends - which the
chancellor has done nothing to discourage - are likely to remain the
preferred option.
Many institutional investors will object on principle to another round of
enhanced scrips, on the grounds that companies are establishing rolling
rights issues in place of cash dividends. Forced to choose between their
principles and an effective cut in dividend, though, pension funds will find
themselves torn.
</TEXT>
<XX>
