<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / The Lex Column: Clarke's promised land
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The equity market's initially warm response to the Budget speech is partly a
mark of sheer relief. There was no hit to pensions, no extension of VAT and
no clampdown on enhanced scrip dividends. But while taxes have been
increased by only Pounds 1.7bn in 1994-95, it requires an act of faith to
believe the government can deliver the spending cuts which constitute the
rest of the deal. For next year these consist largely in lopping Pounds
3.5bn off the contingency reserve, which is all right only as long as the
money does not creep back on to departmental spending totals.
Ultimately, control of spending matters much more to the gilt and equity
markets than the immediate promise of Pounds 7bn of under-funding and
commitment to balance the budget by the end of the decade. On under-funding,
the chancellor did in any case little more than to firm up Mr Lamont's
earlier line, while promises for the millennium may eventually be as
conveniently forgotten as his predecessor's commitment to balance the budget
over the cycle. Mr Clarke, though, seemed apprised of the political
advantages of being seen to tackle the PSBR 'once and for all'. A sense that
grip is being restored may boost the government's standing, helping both
equities and gilts. In theory, the equity market should not be so sanguine
about growth if the PSBR really is to be squeezed. There is not much joy for
consumers. Mortgage interest relief is definitely on the way out. Those who
console themselves with a trip to the sun will find it costs more to drive
to the airport and an extra tenner to take off. Yet Mr Clarke's optimism on
inflation points to further interest rate cuts, while the determination to
boost small companies which pervaded the budget is also encouraging. That
could boost both employment and demand.
</TEXT>
