<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Observer: Out with a bang
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Chinese celebrations will never go with a bang again - at least, not in
Beijing. From midnight, Beijing's 10m residents can no longer ignite their
own fire crackers; from now on firecrackers will only be permitted on
official business.
Not surprisingly, Beijingers are grumbling about the ban, which has been
imposed for anti-pollution and personal safety reasons; hundreds are injured
by fireworks each year.
China invented gunpowder in the seventh century and is the spiritual home of
firecrackers, which the Chinese believe frighten off evil spirits. 'Banning
fireworks is like telling Spaniards they can't have bull-fights, or
Brazilians they are not allowed their carnival,' grouses one Beijing
intellectual.
</TEXT>
