<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Leading Article: Radicalism on the wane
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Is the tide of radical policymaking in the English-speaking world on the
turn? The departure of New Zealand's finance minister Ruth Richardson at the
weekend in a post-election cabinet reshuffle could well be an early warning
signal of a wider trend. Ms Richardson was a key member of the so-called
razor gang, a group of ministers committed to reducing the welfare state.
After an election earlier this month in which the parliamentary majority of
the National party was cut from 34 to one, some weakening of radical resolve
was on the cards.
New Zealand has admittedly been the most extreme of the developed countries
that participated in the renaissance of liberal economic policy since the
early 1980s. As well as a package of wholesale privatisation, labour market
liberalisation and financial market deregulation, the country pushed through
the most comprehensive tax reform of recent years. The head of the central
bank's tenure depends on inflation performance: civil servants too are on
fixed-term performance contracts.
Under both Labour and National party governments, New Zealand has been the
most exciting political and economic laboratory of the OECD area. In less
than 10 years the most regulated, distorted and protected economy in the
24-nation club has become the least regulated, least distorted and least
protected. Yet there have been losers, notably among recipients of social
security, where unemployment benefit and pensions have been cut, and
universal family support abolished. The snag is that radicalism has taken
time to work: growth has been sluggish and unemployment has risen.
Slow-burn
Ms Richardson's departure no doubt reflects the slow-burn nature of the
radical cure. Comparable backlashes are weakening governments elsewhere. Yet
the need for continuing radical action remains overwhelming.
One reason is the growth of structural budget deficits and the narrowing of
national tax bases, as increased capital mobility forces governments into
open fiscal competition. Public spending cuts and higher taxes will thus
remain on the agenda for a long time. Electorates' demand for more
transparent tax systems will become more clamorous. If present high levels
of unemployment in the OECD are to fall, the assault on labour market
rigidities must go on. Inefficiencies in public services need to be
addressed and the process of trade liberalisation must not be allowed to
stall.
Perpetual revolution
Yet the strains inherent in this perpetual revolution in micro-economic
management, with huge shifts in the geographical location of jobs and
industries across national boundaries, make the need for social security all
the more pressing. People are being subjected to greater upheavals, and to
greater uncertainty about jobs and retirement prospects, than at any time
since 1945.
The hostility in the US to the North American Free Trade Agreement was
symptomatic of this sense of insecurity. Election results in the US, UK,
Canada and Australia, as well as New Zealand, have confirmed that the public
will not vote for those who promise higher taxes and reduced public
spending. Yet the appetite for services such as health, education and
pensions remains insatiable.
Radicalism offers an obvious resolution of this dilemma. But when the
constituency for radicalism is weakened in recession and public sector debt
is increasing, damage limitation is the order of the day. The question is
whether this second-best alternative results in a loss of political impetus
that causes the radical bandwagon not merely to slow down, but to go into
reverse.
The Gatt deadline on December 15 provides an early test. In the longer run
the question is whether the combination of weak governments and structural
budget deficits will produce a retreat from the policies that brought
inflation down. What the New Zealand cabinet reshuffle underlines is that
ministerial razor gangs across the OECD area are working with blunter
weapons. A first-world fiscal crisis before the end of the decade cannot be
ruled out.
</TEXT>
<XX>
