<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Letters to the Editor: Unreasonable guarantee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From H R WYNNE-GRIFFITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Mr Whitelam and Miss Webster have missed the point (Letters, November
20). No one is denying that there exist very many pension schemes that are
well funded and could easily pass the solvency test proposed in the Goode
committee report. However, that is not the point; the point is that the
employer has to guarantee that this will always be the case: even at the
expense of all of the shareholders' funds if that's what it takes.
How can company directors guarantee an inflation-related benefit at the
expense of shareholders without calling into question their own duties to
those shareholders and to their company? If this proposal finds itself on to
the statute books, then very many employees are going to find themselves in
pension schemes that are being wound up to be replaced by something that
does not require the guarantee of solvency. This will be to the detriment of
employees' expectations.
By all means have a solvency test and disclose to employees the result, but
it is unreasonable to expect someone to guarantee the future level of
benefits at the expense of somebody else.
H R Wynne-Griffith,
Barnett Waddingham and
Company,
consulting actuaries,
11 Tufton Street,
London SW1P 3QB
</TEXT>
