FT  01 DEC 93 / Letters to the Editor: International safeguards for Thorp
reprocessing plant 'first class'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr R HOWSLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Mr Llew Smith complains that British Nuclear Fuels (BNFL) has
repeatedly failed to provide him with a document on the international
safeguards arrangements for Thorp (Letters, November 23). I am completely
mystified by this.
The document, published by the European Commission, is a public document and
if he cares to ask me for one I will send it to him immediately. When Mr
Smith reads it, he will realise that the international safeguards
arrangements for Thorp are first class and will provide an extremely high
level of independent assurance that the nuclear material, all of which is
for peaceful, civil use, is under proper control.
Indeed, during an international conference in May 1993, senior Euratom
officials concluded that the safeguards techniques implemented in Thorp
provide '. . . a sound system of safeguards activities . . . ensuring that
this major industrial size reprocessing complex can be controlled under
international safeguards to provide a high degree of assurance'.
What else would you expect after an internal technical programme spanning 10
years, detailed discussions over seven years with Euratom concerning
implementation of safeguards, and a four-year international study (Lascar)
involving the US administration and the International Atomic Energy
Authority.
Roger Howsley,
head, security and international safeguards,
British Nuclear Fuels,
Risley,
Warrington,
Cheshire WA3 6AS
</TEXT>
