<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Letters to the Editor: Transported by zone bonds or rates
(2)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DAVID SAWERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your leader on transport in London points the route towards a more
logical method of financing the capital's transport system.
The proposed transport authority for London would be a more plausible
organisation if its functions were extended to cover responsibility for
financing any operating subsidiaries, as well as capital investment, and if
it covered all commuter services into London as well as the transport
services within London.
The performance and charges of the commuter services probably have more
influence than those of transport within London on the attractions of the
city as a place of business. The amount that businesses need to pay their
employees and the value of property in London will be linked to the level of
fares and therefore of subsidies.
The businesses and property owners are therefore the logical sources of any
subsidy to the commuter services, as well as services in London, whether for
operations or investment. So the transport authority would need the power to
levy a 'transport rate' on London business property, which should be an
addition to the standard business rate.
It would also need the power to contract for services with the operators of
British Rail's commuter services and with London Transport. Therefore, it
would take over some of the functions now placed with the franchising
director.
Amendments to the recent legislation on BR would be needed in the act
establishing a transport authority. Ministers might not be welcome such
changes, but they should consider the benefits of shedding responsibility
for transport in London. Local autonomy can have political as well as
economic advantages.
David Sawers,
'Crosby',
10 Seaview Avenue,
Angmering-on-Sea,
Littlehampton,
West Sussex BN16 1PP
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
