<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Letters to the Editor: Transported by zone bonds or rates
(1)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr B D G ANTROBUS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, When I came to Canada in the early 1980s, a combined subway-bus token
cost 35 cents. Now it costs Dollars 1.30. This price has outperformed gold
and other inflation hedges. In London the rise in transport as a relative
price has been even greater.
Here is the answer to the problem of under-investment in transport in
south-east England. Your suggested mega-bond for London (Leader, November
29) should be denominated in zone one rides, and pay interest in zone one
rides, Network SouthEast season tickets, or cash equivalent.
A sum of Pounds 1,000 might buy a 1,000-ride bond offering 50 rides per
annum . . . somewhat like the Wimbledon tennis debentures.
Government need not come into it. A consortium of banks and construction
companies could issue a super financial derivative for Pounds 10bn. They
would negotiate project by project with whoever was running the transport
system: investment for rides of cash equivalent. Uninvested funds would be
placed in medium-dated gilts, from where they probably came in the first
place. It would be privatisation by the back door.
B D G Antrobus,
3266 Yonge Street,
Toronto,
Ontario M4N 3P6,
Canada
</TEXT>
