<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Arts: When political correctness is all - Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last week's schedules were chock-a-block with Aids programmes. Tomorrow
Channel 4 runs more than three hours of Aids programmes. But today there
seem to be no Aids programmes, which is ironic because today is World Aids
Day. Painfully slowly television's treatment of Aids is beginning to change,
but it is an uphill move against entrenched dogma, amour propre and, most
resistant af all, political correctness. Until recently the aim of most Aids
programmes has been, first, to demonstrate the compassion of the producers
and presenters, and, second, to prove that they are not homophobic. Dare to
express the smallest reservations about their assertions that 'Aids is
equally dangerous to everyone, heterosexual as much as homosexual' and you
will be accused of homophobia.
Knee-jerk response programmes are still being made. ITV's Speakeasy Aids
Special on Friday, shown in London and the Midlands, simply began from the
familiar set of assumptions, going out to a nightclub full of young people
'on the pull' to ask whether they were carrying condoms. They found just one
who did, thus bearing out the recent report from a contraceptive
manufacturer (who would doubtless like to increase sales) that only seven
per cent of young people wear condoms with a new sexual partner. Had the
natural journalistic response occurred to the programme makers, they might
have asked: 'Why are people behaving in this way if it is really as risky as
television has always said; could it be that we cried wolf five years ago
when we claimed that within a short time everyone in a major city would know
a heterosexual dying of Aids?' Instead they continued with their
nudge-nudge, wink-wink routine: 'Would you have sex on a first date?' and
'Have you got a condom?'
Aids In A New Light 93, also shown on ITV, this time late on Saturday
evening, was an example of even greater laziness. Instead of making a
programme about Aids in Britain, London Weekend bought a secondhand American
programme about the situation in the US. After Elizabeth Taylor's
introductory assertion that the rate of infection is rising sharply every
day, especially among young people and women, other presenters, presumably
famous in the US, came on to declare 'We gotta tell America]' and 'Americans
are very sexy people]' This was not journalism, seeking to tell the truth,
so much as propaganda endeavouring to make a case by selective assertion.
The 'compassionate celebrity' way of covering the subject, with film stars
and disc jockeys adopting deeply concerned expressions as they roll condoms
on to their fingers, is presumably used because television does not dare to
get to the nitty gritty of the Aids phenomenon: sexual practices which are
not usually mentioned in polite society. Among the scores, probably
hundreds, of Aids programmes so far screened I have never yet seen one which
had the courage to say that (leaving aside infected blood banks and needle
sharing) the disease appears to spread where you find (a) a group of
abnormally promiscuous people (b) where anal intercourse is commonplace or
even the dominant practice, the lining of the rectum being more prone to
rupture than the lining of the vagina, allowing the spread of the infection
into the bloodstream, and (c) where either drug abuse or old venereal
diseases weaken resistence to Aids or even provide a vector for the new
disease. Where these three factors coincide, whether among heterosexuals or
homosexuals, Aids will spread quickly unless preventive measures are taken.
As it happens such circumstances have arisen in western industrialised
countries chiefly, if not exclusively, among the gay community. Hence 'gay
plague'.
The preceding paragraph is not a moral judgment, nor a condemnation of any
group. It is a statement of the facts as perceived after reading everything
about Aids that it was possible to lay hands on and which was comprehensible
to the layman. But if you expressed it on one of television's Aids
programmes there would be an outcry, not from the audience, but from the
'agenda setters'. These people - producers, editors, heads of television
departments - believe that it is wrong to tell the public the truth about
Aids because, in their view, the public is already appallingly careless
about 'safe sex' and dreadfully homophobic. Tell viewers the truth and the
heterosexual majority will take this as a signal to forget all thought of
danger to themselves, abandon 'safe sex", and increase the persecution of
homosexuals. In television today it is more important to be seen to be
politically correct than to be seen to be truthful.
And yet things are beginning to look up. To be fair there has always been
one notable exception to the rule: from the beginning Joan Shenton, a lone
independent producer, working with her own company, Meditel, has stuck
insistently to the old idea of journalism, reporting whatever she finds. As
with any subject where there is one overwhelming school of thought and a
number of fringe dissenters you run the risk of becoming identified wholly
and only with the dissenters. Because they are the underdogs and receive so
little attention elsewhere you tend to concentrate on them in an instinctive
attempt to right the balance, whereupon the dominant group anathematises you
and drives you more into exclusive concentration on the fringe.
This is no bad thing, of course, if you see your position as being like that
of Copernicans under the Roman Catholic church or dissidents in Soviet
Russia. Being told 'Any fool can see the sun goes round the earth and your
denial makes you an atheist' or 'any fool can see communism works and your
denial makes you a lunatic' must sound to Shenton very much like 'any fool
can see HIV causes Aids, the pandemic in sub-Saharan Africa proves that
homosexuality is not a factor, AZT is a useful treatment, and your denial
makes you a homophobe'. Previously her work has been shown on Channel 4, but
her Diary Of An Aids Dissident was screened on Monday by Sky News. It told
us more about the propaganda war than about Aids itself, but the revelation
that members of the Aids establishment are now so nervous that they try to
suppress dissident publications suggests that we may be near to a
breakthrough of the truth in the larger public domain.
The weekend also brought The Broadcast Tapes Of Dr Peter, an edited version
of a long sequence of brief reports made for Canadian television by Dr Peter
Jepson-Young, who died of Aids last year. Watching the progress of the
disease and this man's reaction to it was, surprisingly, a most moving and
uplifting experience. He met blindness with apparent calm and set about
learning to play the piano. He acquired a guide dog, then had to resort to a
wheelchair with the dog trotting alongside. He organised a 'live will' and
discussed the details of his own death with family and friends, joking about
spending his final hours in a four-poster bed with velvet covers. His
reports were not always so upbeat, but as an exhibition of the strength of
the human spirit this was an extraordinary programme.
Best of all, perhaps, in terms of journalism - though we shall have to see
more before being certain - is Channel 4's set of four documentaries, The
Plague, made by George Carey and Ann Moir, of the independent company
Barraclough Carey. The opening episode, 'Zero Factor', looked back to the
early 1980s and the emergence of a terrifying unknown disease among the
homosexual communities which used the bath houses in California and Fire
Island in New York. By tracking the people centrally involved (not just
sufferers, but public health officials and volunteer workers) the producers
created one of those real-life detective stories which are almost
embarrassingly gripping, given that we know the outcome and the seriousness
of the subject.
If this series brings the same sort of workmanlike approach to such matters
as the African phenomenon and even to the over-arching question of the
relationship between HIV and Aids, then television will at last be able to
start holding up its head in an area where, previously, it should have hung
it in shame.
</TEXT>
<XX>
