<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It may be necessary to restrain FT ballet critic Clement Crisp during
tonight's three-hour Winter Gala marking the centenary of Tchaikovsky's
death. Not only is contortionist Sylvie Guillem dancing, but her piece, 'La
Luna', was choreographed by Maurice Bejart, one of Crisp's betes noires.
Other dancers include Leanne Benjamin and Tetsuya Kumakawa in excerpts from
'Nutcracker", and Darcey Bussell and Zoltan Solymosi in a Balanchine pas de
deux. Singers include Placido Domingo and Kiri Te Kanawa (BBC2, 7.30 ).
You might have thought it paradoxical that a visual medium such as
television should draw so many of its 'personality' presenters from among
those with weird voices, yet it is so: think of David Bellamy and Lloyd
Grossman. Now art critic Brian Sewell, who sounds like a walking parody of
Noel Coward, is joining their ranks. He presents Travelog and 'goes in
search of the art of Bavaria, taking in the perils of Munich's one-way
system and the castles of Ludwig II, the 'mad king', on his way to the
galleries and exhibitions' (C4, 8.30).
