<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Management: Who will buy the Citizen's Charter? - The global
market for UK ideas of public service reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is probably too soon to say that the Citizen's Charter has won popular
acclaim in the UK. It will take many more years to convince the sceptics
that the government's initiative for improving the quality of public
services is more than a cosmetic exercise.
But there is considerable interest throughout the world in the ideas behind
the charter, and in ways of making public services more responsive to their
customers. From Argentina to Zimbabwe, governments are looking for ways of
improving service quality while bearing down on costs.
And with Britain ahead of the field, at least for the moment, selling the
know-how of the Citizen's Charter offers a new export industry for
management consultants and training organisations.
Peninah Thomson, a management consultant with Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the
accountants, has already sold the idea to Kuwait. For the last year, she and
a team of consultants have been helping Kuwaiti ministers and civil servants
think more about their customers.
Thomson is convinced that the charter approach could be a valuable invisible
export. 'We've invented a better mousetrap in public administration,' she
says. 'The world is beating a path to our door.
'Kuwait could have chosen an American model of admini-stration, but chose
ours instead.'
Further work may follow in other Gulf countries, such as Dubai, which have
seen what the initiative means in Kuwait. The government of Hong Kong has
also run a programme to improve the quality of its public services.
Ripa International, part of the Capita Group, is another training and
consultancy company which helps public administrators learn the charter
techniques for use in their own countries. Sierra Leone, South Korea and
Indonesia are among 60 countries which have sent civil servants on courses
to learn more about UK government reforms.
This week, a group of fast-stream trainees from the Polish civil service is
in London for training, a symptom of the growing interest in better quality
public services in eastern Europe.
The Cabinet Office unit which manages the Citizen's Charter has received a
stream of queries from more than 40 countries interested in the UK approach.
According to Diana Goldsworthy, the unit's deputy director, these range from
'the guy from Zimbabwe who wants an hour to chat about improving public
services, to the South Australian state government which has unveiled its
own Citizen's Charter.'
Close links have also been developed with the US, where vice-president Al
Gore heads a drive to 'reinvent' the federal government machine.
A two-day conference on Service for the Citizen, staged by the unit last
December, attracted participants from more than 20 countries. A second
conference next month will compare the experience of Australia and the US
with that of the UK and other European countries.
What impresses other governments is the simplicity of the UK approach.
'There's no high-flown theory behind the Citizen's Charter,' says
Goldsworthy. 'It simply looks at the needs of the consumer of public
services and finds ways of satisfying those needs.
'It is pragmatic and flexible, and it hasn't required a great deal of
legislation to implement it. The unit manages the charter as a project,
using techniques which can be transplanted anywhere.'
Thomson believes that more could be done to sell British expertise abroad.
Greater collaboration is needed between the Cabinet Office which has
developed the ideas, the Foreign Office which represents Britain overseas
and the companies which can help in implementing Citizen's Charter-type
programmes.
'There's a huge interest out there in something Britain's got to offer,' she
says. 'We need to work together so that more countries can buy the UK model
of public sector reform.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    KWZ  Kuwait, Middle East.
</CN>
