<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Management: When seniority is replaced by merit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Even if it confirmed a trend which had already started, the lead article
several weeks ago on the front page of the Nikkei, Japan's national economic
daily, is likely to have shaken many loyal Japanese businessmen.
Nissan, Japan's second largest vehicle maker, it reported, would abolish
seniority-based pay for nearly 3,000 managers and would be putting them on a
performance-related pay scheme.
The news that one of Japan's most prominent industrial groups was planning
to do away with the cherished tradition of seniority was a clear signal to
Japan's hard-working salarymen that the secure life of ever-rising incomes
could no longer be taken for granted.
Nissan is not alone in trying to restructure its salary system. A growing
number of Japanese companies is experimenting with schemes that allow
salaries to reflect better an employee's performance. Fujitsu, for example,
is trying to do this with the bonuses its managers receive twice a year.
Honda, the car maker, adopted an annual salary system last year whereby pay
is linked to performance in the previous year. The trend is being spurred by
changes in the Japanese economy and in the working environment, says
Haruyoshi Nishio, general manager in the Human Resources Department at
Marubeni, the trading house.
The Japanese system of paying employees according to seniority worked well
for companies while the economy was growing. It fostered corporate loyalty
and allowed companies to repay that loyalty in the form of increasing
salaries. Seniority was also a method of assessing an employee's
contribution to the company and complemented the Japanese belief in the
value of experience and in wisdom in old age.
But it also created a cosy environment in which mediocrity was condoned.
Since employees' basic salary increased each additional year they worked
with the company, there was little incentive, in terms of pay, to do more or
better.
Katsuhiko Sato, deputy general manager of the company's personnel
department, points out the maturing of the Japanese economy and the ageing
population have undermined the seniority-based pay system in recent years.
At the same time, length of service and hours of work do not necessarily
lead to better performance in a world where value-added work has
increasingly taken over from mass-volume production.
'It may have been true with factory work in the past but is not necessarily
true with many of the jobs performed today,' says Yuri Momomoto, manager of
public relations at Fujitsu. 'In software, for example, some people can
write a programme in a few days while others will take weeks.'
Better employee motivation obviously lies at the heart of many of the
changes. But companies are conscious of the need to ensure that performance
is measured as objectively and fairly as possible. To do so they have
introduced systems for employees to agree performance targets with their
superiors and jointly assess the results at the end of the fiscal year. In
public relations, for example, a department head might agree with a superior
to approach new publications, or sponsor innovative seminars to spread
knowledge of the company and its products. At the end of the year, they
would discuss whether these targets had been successfully reached. Setting
such targets not only provides managers with some objective measurement for
performance but also helps to clarify an employee's job aims.
'During the years of high growth, the goal was always the same and very
clear: to sell more products,' says Shin Tanaka, manager of public relations
at Honda. 'But as growth has slowed, the goal is no longer as clear and that
is why the productivity of white collar workers seems so low.'
One lingering fear even among companies that have embraced
performance-related pay, is that the greater emphasis on individual
performance could destroy the group harmony that has served Japanese
companies so well in the past.
Nevertheless, the move by some companies to introduce merit as a barometer
for pay indicates Japanese employment practices face a significant turning
point as companies struggle to adapt to an economic environment markedly
different from the growth years that formed the basis for those practices in
the first place.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8741 Management Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-5192</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLACGABQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Management: Costly burden of tradition - Japan's custom of
lifetime employment in return for total loyalty is being questioned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Corporate Japan's social contract, of a job for life in return for perpetual
loyalty, is coming under question from both sides.
A growing number of industrial companies are seeking job reductions among
their loyal staff, or moving redundant people to other divisions, in an
attempt to cut wage costs during the recession. For them, the tradition of
lifetime employment is becoming a costly burden as the rising yen pushes up
costs against foreign competitors.
At the same time, more employees, especially the young, are starting to
accord more importance to their own interests than the company's. Only 20
per cent of staff over 50 have any other interest in life beyond working for
the company, but this rises to 38 per cent for 30-year-olds and 43 per cent
for 20-year-olds, according to a survey by the Economic Planning Agency.
A look at how the management of two very different groups, Toyota, Japan's
largest car maker and Mitsubishi Materials, a leading metals and ceramics
supplier, respond to these pressures shows that employment structures are at
the start of a slow evolutionary change.
Toyota started to adjust the social contract last June, when it shifted 20
per cent of its 4,000 white collar administrators into new project
divisions, such as strategic planning, environmental assessment or working
with suppliers.
The move, part of a wider cost-cutting drive, involved no redundancies as
might have been the case if Toyota were a western car maker, so it is only a
minor adjustment to the social contract. But it is the first time that
Toyota has asked staff to take such a step. 'The moves are still at an early
stage, but there have been no special difficulties,' says Iwao Isomura,
vice-president for personnel.
In parallel, Toyota is seeking to employ more people who will stay with the
group for only a short time, to improve cost flexibility and to gain access
to experts in technologies new to the car industry. 'Maybe it is a good idea
to have two types of employees, a stock type and a flow type,' says Tatsuro
Toyoda, group president. Although the company regularly employs temporary
seasonal workers at its factories, as one of Japan's blue-chip companies,
lifetime employment would be the rule for its white collar staff.
Putting this philosophy into practice will, however, be very slow. The
Japanese education system does not favour the type of person who wishes to
map out his own career, says Isomura.
Moreover, flexible employment can only work at Toyota if other Japanese
companies follow suit, so that staff on the move can find new jobs
elsewhere. A handful are thinking along the same lines, including Sony, a
perennial Japanese management trendsetter. But some older industrial
companies believe Japan should not challenge traditional employment
structures lightly.
Mitsubishi Materials is a classic example. 'Sony and Toyota are both
post-war creations. Our philosophy, as a company with pre-war origins, is
very different,' says Takeshi Nagano, chairman of Mitsubishi Materials and
president of the Nikkeiren employers' federation. 'People work for us all
their lives partly because they know their incomes will rise as they grow
older. But we also have a kind of family atmosphere, special to the mining
industry, which is one of the origins of Japanese industry,' he says. 'It
makes for very stable corporate planning, even if it is not so easy in a
recession,' he says.
The tradition of lifetime employment will change, he accepts. But it will
take a generation - so expect no revolutions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Mitsubishi Materials.
    Toyota Motor Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
