<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Railtrack pressed on Scottish line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack, which will run Britain's rail infrastructure from next April, is
to be pressed to electrify a line between Edinburgh and Glasgow to test
government willingness to fund rail projects that do not produce an adequate
rate of return.
A study by consultants Oscar Faber TPA presented yesterday showed that
electrifying the route via Falkirk, the commuter line between the two
cities, was the best option for its future. It would attract passengers from
the roads, the consultants said.
While it would not meet the government's required 8 per cent rate of return
on investment, a good case could be made for seeking a government grant when
social and non-user benefits were taken into account, the study said.
Mr Paul Prescott, director of Railtrack Scotland, said that if the project
were evaluated on the same basis as a road scheme 'it would come out almost
higher than upgrading the M8 motorway' between Edinburgh and Glasgow.
In its rail privatisation white paper last January, the government said it
was 'ready to provide support for investing in the railway for schemes
which, although not earning an adequate financial return, provide a
substantial cost-benefit return when wider benefits are taken into account'.
Electrifying the 47-mile line would cost about Pounds 75m, of which Pounds
50m would be spent on new trains. The 100mph trains would run every 15
minutes instead of the present 30 minutes, and permit a journey time of 44
minutes compared with the present 50 minutes.
The study was commissioned by ScotRail and Strathclyde, Central and Lothian
regional councils, which want to contain road congestion.
ScotRail and the councils will now press the government through Railtrack to
help finance the project.
The initial approach will be to the Scottish Office. Mr Cyril Bleasdale,
director of ScotRail, said a decision was unlikely for two years. 'It's a
vision and a long-term strategy,' he said.
Mr Malcolm Waugh, chairman of Strathclyde regional council's transport
committee, said it would be 'a test case of the government's new policy'.
</TEXT>
