<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Counties review dubbed 'a mess'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's decision to make the Local Government Commission for
England conduct a further review of councils in Derbyshire and County Durham
could itself be open to judicial review, it was said yesterday.
Mr Jack Straw, the shadow local government minister, described the review as
a 'mess'. He said: 'The reference back of Durham and Derbyshire and not of
Cleveland appears to be a highly partisan move which could well leave the
secretary of state (Mr John Gummer, environment secretary) open to judicial
review.'
Plans to restructure all three counties were unveiled this month by the
commission. However, the government announced a change to its guidance for
the commission in September, which made it clear that it expected the
two-tier status quo of counties and districts to be replaced by unitary
authorities.
Mr Straw said Cleveland, which is Labour-controlled and is to be split into
four unitary authorities, might have a case for judicial review because it
will not be re-examined by the commission.
Mr Dennis Pettit, chairman of the Labour-controlled Association of County
Councils, said the move over Derbyshire and County Durham called the
independence of Sir John's commission into question.
The cross-party Association of District Councils, though, said it signalled
the end for the two-tier status quo.
</TEXT>
