<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Recovery uneven in east Midlands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Small quoted companies in the east Midlands are trailing large groups in
recovery from recession.
Their turnover was static and both pre-tax profits and dividend payments
declined in 1992-93, according to analysis of the performance of the
region's quoted companies by KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountants.
The financial plight of companies with a stock market value of less than
Pounds 50m emphasises the uneven progress of recovery in one of the most
economically diversified regions, where only 21 per cent of total sales of
quoted companies are made overseas compared with 38 per cent of west
Midlands companies.
The KPMG analysis shows that while collectively the region's 71 quoted
companies increased their turnover in 1992-93 by 1.9 per cent, turnover of
the small companies fell by 0.5 per cent. Against a regional average of a
6.9 per cent decline, the operating profits of small companies fell by 71.3
per cent.
Although all quoted companies reduced their debt levels, the poor trading
performance of small companies meant profits covered interest payments only
0.5 times, compared with 6.0 times for large companies.
Overall, companies increased dividend payments by a greater proportion than
the rise in attributable earnings. But, said KPMG, 'the 12 per cent
reduction in dividends paid by small companies has offset reduced profits
and increased dividend cover'.
East Midlands plc by KPMG Peat Marwick, St Nicholas House, 31 Park Row,
Nottingham NG1 6FQ.
</TEXT>
