<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / HK telephone monopoly to end
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Hong Kong government said yesterday that three companies would be
licensed to compete with Hongkong Telecom, the colony's telephone monopoly,
in the provision of local telephone services when the monopoly's exclusive
licence expires in 1995.
Government officials hailed the decision as an important stage in the
implementation of its pro-competition telecoms policy.
After a lengthy review the government decided last year to permit
competition in the local market. Hongkong Telecom retains its monopoly on
international telephony, which generates most of its profits, until 2006.
Mr Gordon Siu, secretary for economic services, said the advent of
competition would enhance Hong Kong's position as a financial and business
centre in Asia and bring substantial benefits to business and residential
telecoms users in the colony.
The award of the licences is, however, subject to the approval of the
Chinese government. Under the terms of Hong Kong's transfer to China in
1997, matters which straddle that year first have to be agreed with Beijing.
It is not expected that China will raise any objection to the three groups
selected to operate competitive services against Hongkong Telecom. The three
large conglomerates - Hutchison Whampoa, Wharf and New World - all have
close links with the Chinese leadership.
The companies plan to compete with Hongkong Telecom in the provision of
niche services for consumers and businesses, mostly video, computer and data
services. Wharf, which also operates a cable television network, will have
the greatest access to the household market of the three.
Analysts said that the advent of competition would not pose a serious threat
to Hongkong Telecom's revenues. Mr Andrew Harrington, telecoms analyst with
Salomon Brothers, said the new entrants would keep the monopoly on its toes,
in terms of the provision of service to customers, and in the future bring
to the market services which are today only embryonic.
