<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Output fall adds to fears on economy: Figures on Japan's
manufacturing, employment and business gloomy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's industrial output fell 5.1 per cent in October, the largest
month-on-month decline on record.
In part, the slide reflected the fall-off from a sharp increase in September
as companies tried to boost output before the end of their half-year
accounting period.
But it was only one of several figures published yesterday which added to
doubts about the country's economic recovery.
Deteriorating conditions of the labour market were highlighted in a 2.7 per
cent rise in unemployment in October, a six-year high. The ratio of job
offers to job seekers fell to a six-year low of 0.67, that is, 67 jobs for
100 seekers.
A quarterly survey of business conditions by the Ministry of International
Trade and Industry indicated that 65 per cent of more than 160 leading
Japanese companies did not expect a business recovery until late 1994 or
later. Only 15 per cent forecast a recovery in conditions in the next six
months.
The Nikkei 225 average, which plunged to a year's low Monday, recovered
327.83 points, or 2 per cent, to 16,406.54 after government officials and
financial authorities yesterday pledged to implement measures to boost the
economy.
Mr Yasushi Mieno, Bank of Japan governor, said the central bank was ready to
take additional monetary action if the underlying economic conditions
warranted.
Ms Manae Kubota, director general of the Economic Planning Agency, called
for income tax cuts and an expansionary budget for the next business year to
support consumer spending, while Mr Hirohisa Fujii, finance minister, and Mr
Hiroshi Kumagai, minister of international trade and industry, said the
government would consider easing land taxes and action to reinvigorate the
property market.
The worsening economic outlook came as parliament began debate on the
supplementary budget announced in September.
Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, prime minister, may be forced to extend the
parliamentary session as approval of the budget is likely to take about a
week, blocking discussion of his political reform package in the upper house
of the Diet until December 8.
Mr Hosokawa has pledged to introduce political reform bills before December
15.
</TEXT>
