<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / France and Britain in EU airlines rift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France said yesterday it had won majority support in the European Union for
its efforts to blunt airline deregulation in order to bail out financially
stricken flag carriers. But others at the Brussels meeting of transport
ministers disputed the claim.
Although France said nine of the 12 backed its proposals, four European
Union member states - the UK, Germany, the Netherlands and Denmark - took
the rare step of dissociating themselves from the conclusions to the debate
on the future of civil aviation published by the Belgian presidency of the
EU.
The 12 agreed to try to repair the growing EU rift over the airline crisis
at a special meeting in Athens on February 7, by when the 'committee of wise
men' set up by the European Commission to examine the industry will have
reported.
Transport ministers will then try to agree a policy when they meet in April.
France came to yesterday's meeting seeking a relaxation of EU rules which
prevent airlines from sharing capacity, a freeze on air traffic fees, and EU
funding to speed up the pace at which older aircraft are taken out of
service. The UK led the opposition, calling for a ban on state aid to flag
carriers, and arguing against any retreat from Europe's 'open skies' regime.
By lunchtime Mr Bernard Bosson, France's transport minister, declared that
Britain was 'absolutely isolated'. He said that for France 'there is no
question of turning back' on liberalisation. But if Europe wanted to retain
an airline industry, it could not jump 'from protectionism into a jungle of
ultra-liberalism'.
Mr Bosson claimed that Germany had swelled its 9-3 majority against Britain.
Bonn, he said, backed French calls for implementation of safeguard clauses
on overplied routes; accepted the idea of funding to withdraw old aircraft,
but on environmental grounds; and sought 'moderation' rather than a freeze
on air traffic fees.
His statement was strongly denied by a senior German official, who said: 'We
are much closer to the British than the French on this.' He confirmed
Germany had refused to endorse the Belgian presidency document, which raised
the prospect of EU funding and invited member states to invoke safeguard
clauses on capacity-sharing.
The clauses admit the possibility of airlines clubbing together to reduce
flights and share out passengers if all carriers on a particular route are
losing money.
One UK official said the French 'were at a different meeting'.
</TEXT>
