<TEXT>
President Carlos Salinas has reshuffled his cabinet in the wake of the
nomination of Mr Luis Donaldo Colosio as his party's presidential candidate
for next year. Mr Manuel Camacho, the powerful mayor of Mexico City and
rival to Mr Colosio, was appointed minister of foreign relations, a post
that takes him away from the centre of the political stage in the run-up to
the election.
Mr Ernesto Zedillo, who resigned as education minister to become Mr
Colosio's campaign manager, was replaced by the foreign relations minister,
Mr Fernando Solana. Mr Zedillo, a former budget minister and central bank
official, in effect, becomes Mr Colosio's closest aide. His presence may
reassure investors concerned about Mr Colosio's experience in economic
policy.
Mexico's ruling party has claimed victory in the gubernatorial election in
the state of Yucatan, although official results are not expected until
today. The centre-right opposition has accused the party of fraud, and is
preparing to protest against alleged vote-rigging in rural parts of the
state.
