<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Italian unions to stage jobs protest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's engineering unions have called out 400,000 workers for a one-day
strike on December 10 in protest at growing unemployment.
The strike call comes as Fiat said it would cut its workforce by 5 per cent
and Olivetti, the computers and office equipment group, said it wanted a
further 2,000 job cuts among its 18,500 Italian workers.
The move underlines growing levels of labour unrest in different sectors of
the economy in the run-up to Christmas. Last night petrol pump operators
began a three-day strike; and throughout the rest of the week stoppages have
been threatened by various groups of employees in air transport.
Unemployment, now close to 11 per cent of the working population, has
particularly hit the engineering and metal-working sectors. The unions say
the recession is so severe that the Ciampi government must consider
reducingthe 48-hour working week and resort to 'solidarity contracts' - a
formula which permits work-sharing arrangements and temporary reductions in
working hours.
At the same time the unions are anxious to instil in both the government and
among Confindustria, the industrialists' association, a greater strategic
view of industry. The issue of excess labour, they say, must first be
considered with in the broader context of Italy's industrial policy and
priorities. The employers, they claim, are far too concerned with the
mechanics of job cuts and plant closures.
A tripartite approach to industrial strategy was agreed in the July 23
accord between the government, Confindustria and the unions on pay and
productivity.
However, the unions maintain the July pledges have largely been ignored,
especially regarding investments in research and development.
The engineering unions have traditionally been the most influential in
shaping industrial relations. Next week's strike will cover 250,000 in the
private sector and a further 160,000 in state-run industries. The strike
will extend to Fiat plants which have in recent years tended to ignore such
calls.
The Fiat, in announcing its redundancy and lay-offs plan last week, rejected
the idea of a reduced working week. However, the unions fear the parlous
state of the domestic and international vehicle market will provoke more
redundancies. Fiat this year will be producing 1.2m cars against a capacity
of 2m, which will rise to 2.4m next year.
</TEXT>
