<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Tietmeyer in prices warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The recent decline in west German inflation will be slowed next year by
rising charges for local government services and indirect taxation, Mr Hans
Tietmeyer, Bundesbank president, warned last night. The central bank would
remain alert to guard against any danger of a more general increase in
prices, he told economists in Zurich.
However, he indicated that the central bank believed the monetary situation
was stabilising. Money supply growth had been following a 'more normal'
route for several months, he said, and had moved 'strongly' towards the
upper end of its target range since the summer.
The prospects for prices were brightening. The November cost of living index
had shown a year-on-year increase of 3.7 per cent, and in the last three
months consumer prices had risen at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
around 2.5 per cent, he said.
He reminded his audience that the central bank had started reducing interest
rates last autumn when, although money supply was far above target,
prospects for inflation were improving.
Mr Tietmeyer claimed current policy, although based firmly on the growth of
money supply, was flexible and never driven by parochial considerations. 'We
do not try to hold money supply on course, come hell or high water, in the
short term,' he said. 'Missing targets does not automatically lead to money
policy feedback.'
His remarks, two days before the Bundesbank central council is due to meet
and consider interest rates, seem likely to encourage expectations of a
reduction in the internationally-sensitive 5.75 per cent discount rate.
Private-sector economists, despite being regularly caught wrong-footed by
council decisions, expect a further reduction either this week or on
December 16, the date of the last Bundesbank meeting this year, at which a
key task will be to set targets for money supply growth in 1994.
Underlying inflation is forecast to ease markedly next year as a result of
real pay cuts across much of industry. Forecasters have been encouraged by
individual deals such as that at Volkswagen where a nominal pay cut of 10
per cent has been accepted.
</TEXT>
