<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Premiers 'knew of illicit funding'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Two former Christian Democrat prime ministers of Italy knew about the
large-scale illicit financing of the party, a Milan court heard yesterday.
Mr Severino Citaristi, party treasurer from 1986 until March this year, made
the accusations against Mr Ciriaco De Mita and Mr Arnaldo Forlani. It is the
first time in a court that a Christian Democrat party leader has been said
to have had direct knowledge of illicit financing.
Mr Citaristi has received 64 separate notices of investigation from 12
different sets of magistrates for corruption and illicit financing - the
most of any single politician in the corruption scandals. He has not denied
the charges but refused to accept political responsibility for his illicit
money-collecting activities.
Yesterday he described his activities when he gave evidence in the trial of
Mr Sergio Cusani, a politically influential consultant close to the
Socialist party who is alleged to have handled part of the L150bn (Pounds
60m) bribe paid by Ferruzzi-Montedison to arrange the reorganisation of the
petrochemicals industry - the so-called Enimont affair.
Mr Citaristi said his party needed up to L65bn in a normal year and L90bn in
an election year, of which half came illicitly. He told the court how Mr De
Mita, then party leader, told him to contact Mr Raul Gardini, then head of
Ferruzzi-Montedison, to obtain a contribution. Mr Gardini handed over L2bn.
Between 1988 and 1992 a further L7bn was paid by the group.
In another development yesterday, the parliamentary anti-Mafia commission
issued an alarming report on the influence of organised crime in the Naples
area. The report specifically identified Mr Antonio Gava, a former Christian
Democrat interior minister and now a senator, as being a key link figure
with the Camorra, the Naples mafia.
Mr Gava, already under investigation for such links, is said to have
organised an influence-sharing deal with crime bosses in the distribution of
L50,000bn funds for the 1982 Irpinia earthquake as part of a ransom for Mr
Cirio Cirillo, a powerful local politician.
The report also detailed the power of the Camorra's 111 clans and 6,700
members. It said 32 municipal councils in the Naples area had been dissolved
for links with organised crime (against 19 in all Sicily), 16 out of 31
magistrates were under criminal investigation; while eight members of
parliament risked prosecution for links with the Camorra.
</TEXT>
