<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Bosnia says partition talks have reached new impasse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Bosnian government yesterday said fresh partition talks had reached an
impasse and accused their Serbian adversaries of hijacking the agenda from
the European Union only hours after the resumption of negotiations among the
republic's three warring parties.
Mr Muhamed Sacirbey, Bosnia's ambassador to the United Nations, warned that
the Geneva talks were in danger of collapse because the Serbs had insisted
on reopening negotiations on Sarajevo.
Before the collapse of peace talks in September, Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald
Stoltenberg, international envoys, had won endorsement from Serb, Moslem and
Croat leaders to place the Bosnian capital under UN administration for two
years.
'Owen is trying to focus on the division of Sarajevo, which is unfortunate,
shameful and counter-productive,' Mr Sacirbey told reporters at the Palais
des Nations in Geneva.
Mr Alija Izetbegovic, the Bosnian president, said there had been 'no
progress' after the close of the first round of talks with Serbian president
Slobodan Milosevic and Mr Radovan Karadzic, Bosnian Serb leader.
Despite the slim hope of reaching a settlement to end 19 months of war, Mr
Sacirbey said the Bosnian government would not abandon peace talks. But he
said the Bosnian delegation had raised a complaint with unnamed parties in
the EU about deviating from the plan proposed by foreign ministers on
Monday.
Lord Owen on Monday said Sarajevo and access to the sea from the Croats
remained the biggest issues, echoing Mr Milosevic's earlier comments.
In recent bilateral meetings, Serb leaders have pushed a 'quality land for
quantity' line in pressing for the exchange of Serb-held districts of
Sarajevo for Moslem enclaves in eastern Bosnia.
</TEXT>
