<DATE>931201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Clarke banks on big spending cuts: Slow-burn tax rises will
take effect as recovery gains pace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke delivered an overtly political Budget yesterday, designed
to boost the nation's finances with big spending cuts and slow-burn tax
rises that will hit large numbers of voters as the economy recovers.
He announced measures to defuse public anger and Tory dismay at earlier
plans to extend value added tax to domestic fuel and power but singled out
home owners, motorists, smokers and holidaymakers for tax increases,
effective mainly from April 1995.
At the heart of Mr Clarke's skilfully packaged Budget was a cut in the
public-sector borrowing requirement next year of about Pounds 6bn, big
public spending cuts and tax rises next year of Pounds 1.68bn to add to the
Pounds 6.7bn planned by Mr Norman Lamont, his predecessor.
Mr Clarke took a calculated gamble with public-sector employees by
announcing tough measures to restrain pay as part of a cash freeze in
government running costs for the next three years.
The chancellor's 'no-nonsense Budget', which for the first time combined
spending and tax-raising, surprised the Commons and financial markets with
its larger-than-expected cuts in public expenditure in 1994-95.
The cuts, he told the House of Commons, were intended to 'sort out the
problem of public borrowing once and for all'. They will 'eliminate
government borrowing entirely by the end of the decade' and 'establish sound
public finances into the next century'.
However, Mr Clarke's confidently delivered first Budget plots only modest
growth of 2.5 per cent for the economy next year although underlying
inflation, at 3.25 per cent, would stay within the 1 per cent to 4 per cent
target next year and fall further later.
His message was warmly welcomed by industrialists and the financial markets,
impressed by the plans to cut public borrowing. The response from some
economists was more guarded. They feared that proposals for higher taxes in
future years would take spending power out of the economy as it tries to
recover from recession.
The chancellor followed the example of Mr Lamont's March Budget by
announcing only modest tax increases for the coming financial year but a
broadening of the tax base to yield big revenue gains in 1995-96 and
1996-97.
From April 1995, mortgage interest relief will be granted at only 15 per
cent, down from 25 per cent at present and 20 per cent due to come into
force next April. Mr Clarke also announced a further cut in the married
couple's income tax allowance from 1995 onwards to 15 per cent from 20 per
cent due to take effect in 1994-95.
But, heeding the Conservative by-election defeats of the past year, Mr
Clarke took elaborate pains to draw the sting for poorer households from the
extension of VAT to fuel and power. Although he announced indirect taxes on
air travel and insurance premiums and increased duties on petrol and tobacco
by well above the inflation rate, the chancellor avoided extending VAT to
exempt and zero-rated goods and services such as newspapers, food and
sewerage charges.
He confirmed that the state pension retirement age for women would rise from
60 to 65 but not before the year 2010.
As befits a self-proclaimed son of the industrial Midlands, Mr Clarke
announced tax and spending measures to help businesses and jobs. He also
announced a crackdown on tax avoidance to yield Pounds 2bn over the three
years and restrictions on unemployment and invalidity benefit intended to
save Pounds 2.5bn annually from the social security budget by 1996-97.
His speech bore witness to his career as a minister in many big spending
departments before he took over as chancellor in May. He appeared more at
ease outlining the government's spending plans than its tax proposals.
The Budget set a PSBR of Pounds 38bn for 1994-95, compared with the Pounds
44bn envisaged in Mr Lamont's March Budget, and forecast a steady decline in
the deficit to Pounds 12bn by 1997-98 and just Pounds 2bn by 1998-99. The
March Budget estimated that the PSBR would still be Pounds 30bn in 1997-98.
He announced a Pounds 3.6bn reduction in the government's public-expenditure
'control total' to Pounds 251.3bn in 1994-95. However, the government did
not raid its contingency reserve to pay for spending programmes. Instead,
cuts in the reserve of Pounds 3.5bn next year and Pounds 3bn in 1995-96 will
be used to reduce overall spending.
Mr Clarke said he expected the Budget would reduce total public spending in
the next three years by about Pounds 10bn below the level assumed in March.
After taking account of the beneficial effects of recovery in the economy to
a growth rate of 2.5 per cent next year and the first half of 1995, 'the
total reduction in public spending over the next three years compared to the
March Budget projections will be no less than Pounds 15bn', he said.
The chancellor added Pounds 1.675m of new taxes to the Pounds 6.73bn already
decided in Mr Lamont's Budget for 1994-95. Mr Clarke's Budget will add
Pounds 4.9bn in taxes to the Pounds 10.3bn agreed in the March Budget for
1995-96 and a further Pounds 6.08bn for 1996-97.
As a result, the share of tax revenue in national income will rise from 36.5
per cent in this financial year to 39.75 per cent in 1996-97. Some of that
may be paid back as tax cuts. One of the justifications Mr Clarke gave for
tackling the public-sector deficit was the government's 'long-term tax
cutting agenda'.
However, the only beneficiaries of tax cuts were businesses. In a move that
will cost Pounds 830m in 1994-95, and Pounds 940m the following year, the
chancellor announced a 0.2 per cent cut in the main rate of employers'
national insurance contributions and 1 per cent reductions in employers'
contributions for staff earning less than Pounds 200 a week.
Lex, Page 16
Editorial Comment, Page 30
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
