<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 93 / Tory applause masks signs of unease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke's gamble that Conservative MPs would unite behind a
package balancing still higher taxes with deep cuts in public spending last
night appeared to have paid off.
The Tory right applauded the additional Pounds 10bn of spending cuts over
three years announced by the chancellor, while those on the party's
centre-left were relieved the burden of the latest tax increases would fall
on the better-off.
But there were signs that the traditional applause on the day for a
'skilful' Budget disguised unease over the implications of a package which
ministers admitted was much tougher than it looked.
In spite of an effective and relaxed performance from Mr Clarke in his
Budget debut, senior ministers left no doubt that they expected the
legislation which would implement the measures to face a rough political
ride.
'He has spread the misery with great skill, but it is still misery,' one
member of the cabinet commented.
The centrist Mr Clarke and his rightwing deputy, Mr Michael Portillo,
launched an immediate campaign to persuade their allies on different wings
of the party that the package had to be accepted in its entirety to preserve
the political balance. Mr Portillo, the heir apparent of the Thatcherite
right, saw his already rising political star boosted by the scale of the
spending cuts.
Mr Clarke told a crowded meeting of Tory backbench MPs that the measures to
cut decisively the budget deficit represented the final piece in the jigsaw
needed to ensure a steady recovery in the government's political fortunes.
The implication was that if the party took tough decisions now, there could
yet be scope for reductions in the basic rate of income tax before the
general election due by mid-1997.
A relatively generous compensation package to ease the introduction of value
added tax on domestic fuel also appeared likely to defuse the threatened
rebellion on the Conservative benches over an issue that has dogged the
government for nine months.
There was also palpable relief that the chancellor has not extended VAT into
areas such as food and children's clothing, and applause for the series of
measures to help small businesses.
A new child care allowance for single parents and an increase in tax
allowances for the blind were carefully designed to reassure the party left
that tougher rules on other benefits did not signal a move to dismantle the
welfare state.
Deep cuts in the defence budget, the proposed cuts in invalidity and
unemployment benefits, a sharp rise in petrol tax and a levy on insurance
premiums were all identified as potential political flashpoints.
Mr Clarke skilfully dispersed the tax rises across a range of measures to
avoid a focal point for a backbench rebellion comparable to the uproar
caused by the extension of VAT on fuel.
But ministers acknowledged the freeze on income tax allowances, higher
petrol prices, the new insurance and airport taxes and the further cut in
mortgage interest relief would hit directly the Conservatives' traditional
supporters in the shire counties.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, signalled the start of an opposition
onslaught on the government's 'broken tax promises', charging that
taxpayers, the disabled and unemployed were being made to pay for the
government's economic incompetence.
Labour calculated the cumulative tax increases since last March would cost
the average family Pounds 10 per week from next April and Pounds 16 per week
from 1995.
The additional cuts assume the government can stick to a freeze on public
sector pay next year, a policy likely to be threatened by industrial
discontent in the main public services.
</TEXT>
