<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (31): One is now a better
person
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERSONAL IMPACT: THE ART OF GOOD COMMUNICATION
by Michael Shea
Sinclair-Stevenson Pounds 17.99 196 pages
The bookshops of the world, claims Michael Shea, former press secretary to
the Queen, overflow with personal improvement texts of highly questionable
quality. Quite so.
Shea's own addition to some already groaning shelves is a disappointing
effort in which the blindingly obvious has been dressed up in dubious jargon
designed to grace it with some authority.
His work is hailed by the publishers as a manual bursting with hints
intended to improve the reader's personal impact in a 'media democracy'
where all-important impressions are formed and fixed in 15 seconds. So never
slouch, don't fiddle, don't ramble, avoid sweaty palms and don't get too
close if you've got halitosis. Shea begins profoundly, by suggesting that
the most successful people in corporate and public life are those who know
best how to communicate. He then conjures up three characters who he
subjects to a series of career challenges, ranging from job interviews to
public speaking and media interviews.
John Hustle is brash, pushy and glib with 'a carpet salesman's answer to
everything' while Alan Grey is quiet, a little scruffy and a bit of a
non-entity. David Wright is the clever-clogs of the bunch, smiling
agreeably, well-groomed and oozing confidence. He is presented as 'the man
most likely to' but is likely to be about as popular around the office as a
time-and-motion study expert.
Here is a book stuffed full of paralanguage, eyelock, language acquisition
devices and inter-personal communication techniques. Cut away the
technospeak and what do you get? If you are addressing an audience and
people look puzzled, you have to say more; if they are upright and alert,
you can rest assured you have their attention.
If you want to get the low-down on someone in order to work out how best to
interact with them, then study their handbags, suits, necklines and beards
(hopefully not all found on the same person).
Anyone who is still trawling up the infamous pre-election television debate
between sweaty, shady Richard Nixon and John F Kennedy Shea, the
president-to-be with 'the tingle-tongue taste' smile, in order to
demonstrate the dangers of television, must be in dire trouble.
The author calls in aid everyone from Demosthenes to Talleyrand and, in a
more contemporary - though no more relevant - vein, the likes of Michael
Jackson, Maddona and Mrs Thatcher to drive home his messages. He ends with
'form reports' on public figures like Labour leader John Smith ('flat and
boring' paralanguage), John Harvey-Jones ('very colourful ties') and Jeremy
Paxman ('supercilious, arrogant, almost facetious'). Very perceptive.
Shea says his is not a 'how to' book but more a reference chart which may be
useful in developing your overall impact. He claims the skills set out can
make the difference between success and a life of missed opportunities.
The overriding impression left, however, is that anyone who requires such
fundamental advice can't really believe they have a hope in hell of aspiring
to be stand-in chauffeur, never mind chief executive.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
