<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (29): What about the
workers?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOCIAL DIMENSION: EMPLOYMENT POLICY IN THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITY
by Michael Gold (editor)
Macmillan, Pounds 13.99 276 pages
Underlying the debate about European-wide employment regulation lie a series
of controversial assumptions about the relationship between labour market
systems and economic performance.
The fundamental assumption, shared by most of the Christian and Social
Democrats who run the European Commission, is that the relative economic
success of northern European countries such as Germany and Holland has been
achieved because of, not in spite of, their systems of labour regulation and
integration.
This view is challenged by many of Europe's economists as well as most of
the British Conservative party, who view such arrangements as hopelessly
inflexible.
Even an open-minded Conservative who did accept that the strong voice of
German labour, tempered by strict legal restraints, has contributed to high
productivity and wage discipline in Germany, would still reject such a model
for Britain.
Britain, the argument might run, has always had an open, volatile economy
and therefore needs a flexible 'hire and fire' labour market, especially if
it is to compensate for low labour mobility and low educational standards.
To a surprising extent this 'horses for courses' argument is now accepted by
the EC, as Michael Gold recognises in his introductory essay to The Social
Dimension.
The 'Germanic' model of industrial relations no longer directly inspires EU
employment legislation as it did in the late 1970s when workers on company
boards was first proposed. Despite British complaints that Brussels is
trying to impose a 'continental' model of labour regulation on the UK, the
Commission is now far more sensitive to the subsidiarity argument in
national labour markets.
Since the late 1980s the argument for Europe-wide legislation has shifted.
At one level it has become more political - the single market has given
capital new advantages, so there must be something for labour too, hence the
1989 Social Chapter.
But as Europe's economies have become more integrated, the primary concern
has been to prevent a downward spiral of competition over labour conditions
 -so-called 'social dumping'. There is little hard evidence that such
dumping is on the increase, but it is a possibility as barriers fall.
These essays do not analyse such assumptions in depth. Essentially they
provide a textbook describing the minutae of institutions and existing
legislation, especially in the three key areas where the EU's minimum
standards really do make a difference to working life: health and safety,
equal pay and redundancies.
The essays offer a useful historical perspective. Gold, for example, points
out that the arguments between neo-liberals and regulators go back to
Article 117 of the original Treaty of Rome.
The Article argued that the condition of labour would improve spontaneously,
encouraging the harmonisation of 'social systems' as a result of the common
market. The same Article argued, however, that regulation and
'administrative action' was required to ensure those outcomes.
Finally, although much of the book's technical detail will still be relevant
in 10 years time, it was completed before the Maastricht Treaty was
ratified, so it already feels out of date.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-5259</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLACFAH0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (28): A requiem for Sweden -
Robert Taylor reflects on the death of a social model
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LIMITS OF SOCIAL DEMOCRACY: INVESTMENT POLITICS IN SWEDEN
by Jonas Pontusson
Cornell University Press Pounds 23.55 261 pages
THE VOLVO EXPERIENCE
by Christian Berggren
Macmillan Pounds 25.00 286 pages
Today's Sweden has become paradise lost for many of its social democratic
admirers. Until recently it was the paradigm of the progressive society,
with a generous welfare state for all, full employment, peaceful industrial
relations and successful global corporations.
Now it looks just another depressed western European economy with soaring
dole queues, a huge public sector deficit, negative growth rates and
plummeting living standards. The gravediggers who have been gathering around
the Swedish Model for over 20 years finally look as if they have a corpse to
bury. Both Jonas Pontusson and Christian Berggren in their differing ways
provide invaluable insights into why the country is no longer what it used
to be. Pontusson's rigorous analysis of investment politics in contemporary
Sweden breaks fresh ground, despite its Marxist framework, by focusing on
the country's powerful private manufacturing sector and its needs on global
markets.
Too often Sweden has been treated in splendid isolation, as a social
experiment on the fringes of northern Europe which could flourish with
little concern for events in the outside world. This was always a false
one-dimensional picture and during the 1980s it became a sad delusion. Under
global pressures the ruling Social Democrats pushed through a perhaps
over-hasty deregulation of its financial system and as a result lost control
of Sweden's economic destiny.
There can no longer be Social Democracy in one country. The country's
economy is now painfully vulnerable to short-term speculation, as was shown
in November 1992 when despite an impressive display of national unity in
defence of the fixed rate of the krona, global forces forced a massive
devaluation.
Pontusson argues convincingly that the once-powerful labour movement was
compelled to recognise its own limitations in the face of capital when the
manual unions pressed from the mid-1970s until the mid-1980s to establish
so-called collective wage earner funds which, in their original version,
aimed at providing the trade unions with a dominant ownership role over
Sweden's corporate investment strategies.
The controversy revealed the strength of the country's private employers,
who mobilised effectively to block such a radical proposal. By contrast, the
manual unions failed to carry their members with them over the issue.
Renowned for their pragmatism and positive attitudes to structural change,
the unions became too ideological and were unable to convince their own rank
and file that the funds were in their own best interests.
However, at the same time the unions were successful in securing legislation
that introduced worker participation into Swedish industry. This was not the
intricate, formalised German model of codetermination and works councils,
but it has provided Swedish employers with an invaluable system to
strengthen workplace support for structural change. Berggren's book on
Sweden is a sorry tale. Volvo under Pehr Gyllenhammar's often visionary but
autocratic leadership became the wonder of the global auto industry as it
abandoned mass production methods at its new plants in favour of
team-working and multi-skilling.
By fusing computer-based technology with labour-intensive craft skills, the
company broke from the old dehumanising methods of the assembly line and
division of labour pioneered by Henry Ford, at least in its new plants
although not in Volvo's homebase in Gothenburg. Industrial sociologists sang
the praises of the Volvo.
Other Swedish enterprises outside auto production followed suit. But their
strategies were not really motivated by altruism. With high worker turnover
and absenteeism in a tight labour market where open unemployment was not a
policy option, they had little obvious strategic choice until the 1980s when
many began - for a variety of reasons - to establish production plants
outside Sweden. Finally, last year Volvo decided to shut its showcase
Uddevalla and Kalmar plants in response to a crisis of excess capacity in a
depressed world market.
The company was keen to emphasise its decision was not a vote of no
confidence by management in the new production methods but a sad consequence
of commercial pressure. But it was always debatable whether the Volvo
methods made financial or industrial sense. In short, during the 1980s the
country could no longer pursue progressive ideas on how to make cars. It
faced increasing market competition where cutting high unit labour costs and
raising productivity were more important than humanising the content of
work.
As Swedes agonise over whether Volvo should become junior partner to
Renault, the French state-run giant, they face the harsh consequences of
being a small open country in a hostile global economy. Having avoided two
world wars and created one of the most enviable of societies, Sweden's luck
may perhaps have run out. These two books provide a nostalgic reminder of
the country's exceptionalism before its fall.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-5260</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLACFAHZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (25): Art for art's sake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ART &amp; BUSINESS
by Marjory Jacobson
Thames &amp; Hudson Pounds 32 224 pages 330 illustrations
A visitor to the First Bank of Minneapolis in the 1980s might have found
himself (or herself) in Controversy Corridor. This is where the art from the
corporate collection was exiled if six or more of the staff found it
distasteful. But, to stimulate thought, the iconoclasts had to justify its
removal from their area.
Dennis Evans took over as president of the Bank just when de-regulation was
churning up the US banking industry. He bought pictures not as an investment
but as a management tool. He believed that an environment of challenging
contemporary art would help his staff abandon past practices and cope better
with new concepts. For a few short years the Bank was one of the main
collectors in the field, amassing 3,000 works by such avant-garde names as
Anselm Kiefer, George Baselitz, and Gilbert and George. It ended in tears.
In 1988 the Bank made a loss of Dollars 310m; Evans resigned; and the
collection was sold.
The experience of the First Bank of Minneapolis can be paralleled throughout
the world. Corporate art is invariably the passion of one senior executive
who is in a position to win over dubious colleagues. The workforce is
usually apathetic; the collections concentrate on the contemporary but soon
become locked in a time warp; initial enthusiasm lapses.
It should not be so. The case for companies to buy art is unassailable.
Redecoration is inevitable when moving to new offices so art can be tax
deductible. In theory it could well prove a good investment. It brightens up
the building and can motivate staff, persuading them that they work for a
go-ahead organisation. It allows the company to glow as the modern patron,
the friend of budding artists.
And yet for every convinced corporate collector, such as Unilever, ICI,
Arthur Andersen, and Fleming's Bank, there are a thousand unaware businesses
surviving in an art-free environment. They might allow themselves a
philistine grin when companies, from Polly Peck to BP, sell off their art
and antiques at a loss.
The fact is that hanging the walls with canvases by Sol LeWitt, and placing
a sculpture by Elizabeth Frink in the reception area, will not automatically
improve productivity or profits. All it does is make a statement about the
company, or rather the view of the company taken by an art-loving director.
And this is how it should be: art for art's sake, not to change the world.
It is sad that few companies have maintained a sufficiently coherent
corporate philosophy to buy art for more than a generation, but that is the
reality that artists must earn to live with.
In Art &amp; Business Marjory Jacobson has travelled the world talking to
companies that do take art seriously. This is not an impartial
investigation, but a polemic. Jacobson is an adviser on art programmes to
companies like AT&amp;T and IBM.
Her book is beautifully illustrated and in its way inspiring. How bold of
BOC to scatter the gardens of its new Surrey HQ with sculptures by Tony
Cragg and Richard Deacon; what a positive statement the installations of
Anish Kapoor in the premises of Starkmann Library Services in London make
about the company.
It would be wonderful if more companies had the confidence to join the club.
But their convictions must be genuine and embrace more than a director or
two. Forcing art into the office environment can be little more than a
gesture. Art &amp; Business wisely avoids examining art as an investment, or
corporate art collections which favour Old Masters and antique furniture. It
is interesting about the corporate museums of Japan and the use of art in
public places. It tells the story of how business should be - sophisticated,
artistically aware, visionary. It should be catalogued under fiction rather
than fact.
</TEXT>
<XX>
