<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (20): The broad ethics of
the free market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ETHICS AND MARKETS: CO-OPERATION AND COMPETITION WITHIN CAPITALIST ECONOMIES
by Colin Crouch and David Marquand (editors)
Political Quarterly/Blackwells,Pounds 11.99 156 pages
The Cold War and communism are over, but the debate over the morality of
capitalism continues. That is the message of this volume of essays, whose
authors are almost uniformly driven by a distaste of capitalism - in its
Anglo-American form, at least.
The distaste is partly a moral one. The authors, who mostly come from the
centre-left of British politics, do not like the way that free markets
produce losers as well as winners. But they also argue that Anglo-American
capitalism, with its stress on competition rather than co-operation, is not
a good way of generating wealth by comparison with the German or Japanese
versions of capitalism.
Their critique of Anglo-American capitalism, though hardly new, has the
advantage of combining 10 authors' perspectives in 150 pages. The heart of
the critique is that long-term relationships cannot develop and flourish in
nakedly competitive markets. What is needed is a culture of community,
co-operation and trust.
The authors argue that the alleged short-termism of the Anglo-American model
is most damaging in three respects. First, the failure to develop long-term
relationships between companies and their shareholders undermines long-term
investment and opens the way for practices such as hostile takeovers and
asset-stripping. Second, the hire-and-fire mentality in the labour market
discourages investment in skills. Third, the fact that manufacturers often
have little compunction about switching suppliers if they can get a better
deal prevents the growth of long-term links between manufacturers and
suppliers.
What all this has to do with ethics? The answer is, in part, that such
long-term relationships have characteristics - trust, loyalty, cooperation
and the like - normally associated with ethical behaviour. But the answer is
also that the practices characteristic of German and Japanese capitalism are
themselves embedded in those nation's broader cultural inheritances.
These cultural linkages are explored in several papers: Ronald Dore's on
Japan; Colin Crouch's on Germany; and Jonathan Boswell's on the links
between Catholicism, Christian Democracy and capitalism in continental
European countries. All three are interesting. But while Dore's and Crouch's
articles are succinct and accessible, Boswell's is hard work.
There is much in the arguments expressed in this volume. Markets do not
exist in a vacuum. They are social institutions and rely on wider cultural
support to function effectively. To appreciate this point, which was
recognised by Adam Smith, one has only to look at the difficulties in
establishing markets in Russia, where the sanctity of contract has no
tradition.
It is also true that markets cannot be divorced from ethical considerations.
Managers, employees, consumers, shareholders and bankers are all human and
their actions are capable of being judged from a moral standpoint. It is not
enough of a justification to say that their actions are designed to maximise
profits.
However, in three ways, the arguments in this volume are deficient. First,
it is misleading to paint capitalism as merely about maximising profits.
Capitalism is a practice with its own entrepreneurial spirit, which values
risk-taking and the creation of value in the widest sense as well as more
narrow profit-making. While Russell Keat, in his paper, acknowledges that
capitalism may be such a practice, these essays in general do not show much
enthusiasm for the dynamic aspects of capitalism.
Second, it is not clear that the Anglo-American model of capitalism has
failed. The recent soul-searching in continental Europe over whether their
markets are too rigid certainly should give pause for thought. While
competitive markets may not be as good in fostering long-term relationships
as co-operative institutions, they may be more flexible in responding to
changing opportunities.
Finally, even if the Japanese and German model of capitalism were superior,
it could not just be grafted on to the British psyche. While several authors
acknowledge this point, there is little exploration of how one could bring
about such a change. That perhaps is material for a second volume.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
