<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (18): Picture this, Mr
Keynes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KEYNES FOR BEGINNERS
by Peter Pugh and Chris Garratt
Icon Books, Pounds 7.99 174 pages
KEYNES is back. Recessions in Germany, Japan and across Europe, sluggish
recoveries in the US and Britain and disillusionment with monetarist
orthodoxy after the collapse of the European exchange rate mechanism have
all helped restore faith in a 'Keynesian' response to recession.
At the root of this revival is a renewed belief that government action is
needed in order to revive depressed economies. But only Japan can be said to
have taken a traditional Keynesian 'pump-priming' response. In the US,
persisting fiscal difficulties combined with heavy private sector debts have
meant that monetary policy has been the main weapon of counter-cyclical
policy.
What would Keynes himself have thought of this new-style activism? For the
causal reader, going back to the often obscure and contradictory works of
the great man himself is unlikely to provide an answer. Nor is the busy
Business Books reader likely to have the time to wade through Lord
Skidelsky's magnificent two-volume biography.
Let me make a suggestion. For those who want a quick flavour of Keynes'
writings, in historical context, with lots of pictures and who are not too
worried about detailed scholarly interpretation, Keynes for Beginners is
perfect. The book traces the history of Keynes' life and thought from his
birth in 1883, through the first world war and Keynes' critique of the
Versailles treaty, the return to the Gold Standard and depression of the
inter-war years, the General Theory of 1936, the second world war and
Keynes' role in establishing the Bretton Woods system, his death in 1946 and
the rise and fall of post-war Keynesianism.
What makes the book novel is its use of illustration and character. Each
page contains just a paragraph of commentary, with the bulk of the analysis
spoken through the mouths of Keynes himself plus a host of characters,
ranging from Adam Smith and Karl Marx, through Adolf Hitler to Margaret
Thatcher and Ronald Reagan. The illustrations are clever, often funny, but
the text is serious and well researched.
Particularly welcome is the contemporary commentary. A rueful John Major
pops up regularly during Keynes denouncement of sterling's disastrous return
to Gold in 1926 at a horribly overvalued rate and subsequent exit. 'Sounds
like the European Community's exchange rate mechanism that we abandoned in
1992]' comments Major. 'I wonder what Keynes would have though of the ERM?'
asks Norman Lamont. 'I give you one guess]' replies Keynes.
</TEXT>
