<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (15): Falling foul of the
fault lines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN CURRENCY CRISIS
by Paul Temperton (editor)
Probus Europe, Pounds 27.50 316 pages
Economically, Paul Temperton points out in his extended introduction to this
volume of collected contributions on the trials of the European Monetary
System, Europe is not a good candidate for a monetary union. Without
effective mobility of labour across borders, and with wages notoriously
inflexible within them, monetary union would create enormous regional
problems. The cost of buying and selling a house ranges between 12 and 22
per cent of the price in France, Italy, Germany and Belgium compared with 9
per cent in the US.
Sir Alan Walters discusses his eponymous 'Walters critique' of the ERM, that
pegging currencies forced governments into perverse domestic monetary
policies: an attempt to run high interest rates to counter high inflation
and monetary growth would invite a deluge of foreign inflows, refuelling
monetary expansion. An ERM-type structure, with fixed but adjustable rates,
is only at best able to offer a knife-edge equilibrium, being inherently
unstable.
With absolutely fixed rates, Walters adds, this would not apply because
domestic monetary policies would have to be surrendered, presumably to the
Bundesbank. Tim Congdon develops this analysis by considering the
differences between domestic monetary frameworks, which meant for example
that in the late 1980s the same interest rates in the UK and Germany led to
a far higher rate of monetary growth in the UK (mainly because of the impact
of the housing market). The ERM was simply incompatible with national
differences in institutional structures and in tax incentives, and
politicians had thought little about the consequences of this.
This book, produced in collaboration with the bond commission of the
European Federation of Financial Analysts' Societies, was originally the
victim of bad timing. The deadline for contributions was last June but the
second ERM crisis, which reached its climax at the beginning of August,
torpedoed its ambitions. However, the publishers managed to capitalise on
the crisis by asking contributors for updates and delaying the publication
date. There was a reasonable degree of co-operation except from the Banque
de France which 'could not provide a contribution which reflected the recent
change in circumstances' and is therefore the only major EU central bank not
to be represented with its own chapter.
Some bitter lessons were learned in August. EU governments were made to
realise that their foreign exchange reserves of some Dollars 275bn counted
for little against global asset portfolios running to trillions and regular
foreign exchange turnover of Dollars 1 trillion per day. There is talk of
the reimposition of capital market controls, but Congdon points out that it
would be an ironic and unsatisfactory outcome if, on the supposed road to
monetary union, EU member states were forced to separate their capital
markets and banking systems.
Although inevitably already a little out of date, this book provides a
varied and expert analysis of the fault lines within the ERM. There are 10
independently contributed chapters on the ERM, the Maastricht Treaty and
central bank independence, and a dozen perspectives from European central
banks, some of which include blow-by-blow accounts of days of crisis.
The latest central bank thinking, judging by recent statements from the
heads of the Bundesbank and the Bank of England, is that member states must
refocus directly on long- term economic convergence and not try to
re-establish the ERM in its old form. Whether this represents the practical
way forward, or simply reflects an attempt by central bankers to push the
problem back to the politicians, is arguable: the desire to converge is much
stronger in some EU member states than others. At any rate, central bankers
have no desire to man any more barricades.
</TEXT>
<XX>
