<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (13): Sex and the class
struggle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEATHERING THE STORM: WORKING-CLASS FAMILIES FROM THE INDUSTRIAL REVOLUTION
TO THE FERTILITY DECLINE
by Wally Seccombe
Verso, Pounds 34.95 286 pages
IN 1973, Aldo Brandirali, Secretary of the Italian Marxist-Leninist Party
gave this advice in the party's official sex guidelines: 'Sex without class
consciousness cannot give satisfaction, even if it is repeated until
infinity.' Now, in Wally Seccombe's difficult book on working-class families
and the fertility decline, Weathering The Storm, it is not the sex but the
class consciousness which is infinitely repeated.
Seccombe continues from his Millennium of Family Change: Feudalism to
Capitalism in Western Europe by looking at working-class families from the
19th and early 20th centuries throughout two industrial revolutions. In the
late 19th century, technological improvements coincided with a decline in
birth rates. The book looks at wages, family structures, prosperity and the
relationship between working and living conditions. It is an inquiry of
broad scope and interdisciplinary method; but the effort required outstrips
the rewards gained in reading it.
Seccombe places family activity (reproduction, sustaining, rest) at the
heart of what he calls 'historical materialism's central theoretical
category.' Crudely, if a Marxist historian wants to account for work and
behaviour in the working-class family and at the same time wants to assume
that the labouring classes are defined by the ruling classes, he will need
some notion of how the working-class family evolves itself.
Seccombe has the answer: 'In order to recognise the deeply reciprocal nature
of this equilibration, and to gauge its resilience or vulnerability, we must
eschew structuralist-functionalist models in which the prevailing mode of
production determines, in a full or sufficient sense, the familial
reproduction of its labouring classes.' And he sets off to explore 'the
potential utility of this revised paradigm for Marxist inquiry' throughout
the next 200 pages of theory and abstraction.
In spite of the difficulty of Seccombe's style, the book has a tight logic
which draws out the initial hypotheses into expanded sections. The section
on 'The Fetishism of the Wage Form and the Concealment of Domestic Labour'
has the familiar air of a male professional academic feeling guilty because
one of the pioneers in the area, Marx in this case, was just not feminist
enough.
The disadvantage of Seccombe's method is that, while academically prudent,
he is empirically jumbled, always carrying on a debate with unseen
detractors while at the same time delivering facts and figures which
non-implicated readers would find useful.
The best chapters are the final two, where Seccombe meets his poor
monosyllabic sources face to face. He looks at patterns of earning in the
second industrial revolution (broadly, around 1870 to 1914) when gas,
chemicals and electricity made a technological impact on an England which
had readied itself for change by building the railways in the 1850s. Here
Seccombe has testimony from women managing on meagre resources and committed
to feeding husband and children first.
The last chapter charts the decline of 'proletarian fertility' from 1890 to
1920 by looking at abortion, birth-control and abstinence. Here, Seccombe
draws on collections of letters to The Women's Cooperative Guild and to
Marie Stopes between 1910 and 1920. At this point, the theory slackens its
relentless grip on Seccombe's material, and individual cries of hurt, need,
pain or joy are heard.
This chapter is much more in line with another book in the same social
history series, Franciose Barrett-Ducrocq's fine Love in the Time of
Victoria: Sexuality, Class and Gender in Nineteenth-Century London which
focuses on evidence from hospital and charity archives.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
