<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (12): Who should really run
the company? - Peter Montagnon reviews the latest thinking on corporate
governance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONTEMPORARY ISSUES IN CORPORATE GOVERNANCE
Edited by DD Prentice and PRJ Holland
Clarendon Press with Allen &amp; Overy, Pounds 35 225 pages
Adam Smith had particularly trenchant views about joint stock companies.
Shareholders, or 'proprietors' as he called them, seldom pretend to
understand the business they invest in and are content to leave its affairs
to the management. The latter cannot be expected to look after other
people's money as carefully as they would their own. Hence his view that
'negligence and profusion must always prevail.'
The argument is equally valid today, though the views expressed in this book
do not necessarily go so far.
Discussion of corporate governance has loomed large in the UK large since
the publication of the Cadbury report. This book provides some useful
insights. But first a word of warning. The trouble with collections of
essays by different people is that they can make for an overall work of
varying quality. This book falls into the trap with a first chapter of
almost mind-numbing turgidity. It is a pity that more effort was not put
into editing, since those prepared to struggle through to subsequent
chapters will find at least part of the experience rewarding.
There are a number of issues to be addressed, not only the search for some
convergence of interest between owners and managers. It is important to
define who are the real stakeholders are in a company, though the idea that
workers are among them belongs perhaps more to the mainland European
tradition. These issues have to be evaluated against a litany of
contemporary concerns: short-termism, investor protection against fraud, and
shareholder democracy, to name but three.
Who should take on the responsibility for ensuring that corporate governance
is sound? Paul Rutteman of Ernst &amp; Young notes that auditors who do not sit
on board meetings cannot have much insight into the actual effectiveness of
non-executive directors. Paul Davies of Oxford University argues that
institutions do not have much of a record for intervening in the way a
company is run. Their main concern is to maximise returns. Intervening to
change corporate policies risks headlong confrontation with management and
requires collaboration between competing institutions.
Perhaps the banks could play a greater role. They often exercise an
important influence through the covenants in their loan documentation. But
as Theodor Baums of the University of Osnabruck notes, the role of banks is
greater still in Germany, where banks wield enormous influence because they
are both lenders and proxy voters of the stock they hold on behalf of
customers. This gives them control of the supervisory board where the real
power within German companies lies.
Curiously, though, German banks can get too close to companies. To ensure
their loans are repaid they have a natural temptation to encourage companies
to gear down and pay small dividends. Once the links are well-cemented,
however, the relationship can be too cosy. Hence they would be reluctant to
insist on management restructuring.
That may be more of a long-term approach but banks may be too risk-averse as
shareholders. The best answer may be a combination of the German system with
that in the UK where there is a market for corporate control which can exert
some pressure on management. How such a compromise would work is the subject
of another book.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
